\u00e9e \u00e0 l'Inde bouddhique |language=fr |trans-title=Around B\u0101miy\u0101n: From Hellenized Bactria to Buddhist India |publisher=De Boccard |editor-first=G. |editor-last=Duc\u0153ur |chapter=Mat\u00e9riaux pour une histoire de la l\u00e9gende et du culte de Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa: une relecture d\u2019un fragment inscrit retrouv\u00e9 \u00e0 Silao (Bih\u0101r) |trans-chapter=Materials for a History of the Legend and Cult of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa: A Rereading of an Inscribed Fragment Found at Silao (Bih\u0101r) |url=https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/17114/1/Tournier%20Kasyapa%20Silao%202012.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619171841/https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/17114/1/Tournier%20Kasyapa%20Silao%202012.pdf |archive-date=19 June 2019 |url-status=live |oclc=823280495}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Tournier |first1=V. |title=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, His Lineage, and the Wish for Buddhahood: Reading Anew the Bodhgay\u0101 Inscriptions of Mah\u0101n\u0101man |journal=[[Indo-Iranian Journal]] |date=2014 |volume=57 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=1\u201360 |doi=10.1163/15728536-05701001|url=https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/18263/1/Tournier%20Mahanaman%20IIJ%202014.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921230648/http://eprints.soas.ac.uk/18263/1/Tournier%20Mahanaman%20IIJ%202014.pdf |archive-date=21 September 2017 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Tsukamoto |first=K. |year=1963 |title=Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa's Precedence to \u0100nanda in the R\u0101jag\u1e5bha Council |journal=Indogaku Bukkyogaku Kenkyu [Journal of Indian and Buddhist Studies] |volume=11 |issue=2 |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921034502/https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |pages=824{{en dash}}817 |archive-date=21 September 2018 |url-status=live|doi=10.4259/ibk.11.824 }}<!--some Japanese journals number their pages in reverse order-->\n* {{Citation |last1=Voros |first1=Sebastjan |title=Mahakashyapa's Smile: Language, Silence, and Mysticism |journal=Synthesis Philosophica |date=January 2014 |volume=58 |issue=2 |pages=387\u2013402 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191449/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649_Mahakashyapa's_Smile_Language_Silence_and_Mysticism |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Welter |first=A. |year=2000 |chapter=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa\u2019s Smile: Silent Transmission and the Kung-an (K\u014dan) Tradition |title=The K\u014dan: Texts and Contexts in Zen Buddhism |pages=75\u2013109 |editor1-last=Heine |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Wright |editor2-first=D.S. |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-802780-5}}\n* {{Citation |first=A. |last=Welter |editor1-last=Buswell|editor1-first=Robert E.|title=Lineage |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|date=2004|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA, [[Thomson Gale]]|volume=2 |pages=462\u2013463 <!-- |isbn=0-02-865720-9-->|isbn=978-0-02-865718-9}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Wilson |first1=L. |editor-last1=Holt |editor-first1=J. |editor-last2=Kinnard |editor-first2=J.N. |editor-last3=Walters |editor-first3=J.S. |year=2003 |chapter=Beggars Can Be Choosers: Mah\u0101kassapa as a Selective Eater of Offerings |title=Constituting Communities, Therav\u0101da Buddhism and the Religious Cultures of South and Southeast Asia |pages=57\u201370 |isbn=978-0-7914-8705-1}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Witanachchi |first1=C.|editor1-last=Malalasekera |editor1-first=G. P. |editor2-last=Weeraratne |editor2-first=W. G. |editor1-link=G. P. Malalasekera |title=\u0100nanda |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Buddhism |date=1965 |publisher=[[Government of Sri Lanka]] |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/231090852/Enceylopaedia-of-Buddhism-Vol-i |volume=1 |oclc=2863845613}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Zurcher |first1=Erik |editor1-last=Williams |editor1-first=Paul |title=Buddhism: Critical Concepts in Religious Studies, 8: Buddhism in China, East Asia, and Japan |date=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |chapter=Buddhist Influence on Early Taoism |isbn=0-415-33234-6 |page=378}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html Mah\u0101 Kassapa, Father of the Sangha], by Hellmuth Hecker, biography based on the [[Pali Canon|P\u0101li Canon]], revised and enlarged translation from Wissen und Wandel volume XXI, number 6, 1975, (German) by [[Nyanaponika]] Thera, The Wheel Publication No. 345, {{ISBN|955-24-0026-0}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190713140808/https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html archived here.]\n* [https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 ''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa''], hosted by Learning Religion, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191247/https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 archived here.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lineage (Buddhism)|Lineage of Buddhist patriarchs]]<br /><small>(According to the [[Zen]] schools of China and Japan)</small>|before=[[Gautama Buddha|\u015a\u0101kyamuni]]<br /><small>Beginning of the lineage</small>|after=[[Ananda]]|years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahakasyapa}}\n[[Category:Foremost disciples of Gautama Buddha]]\n[[Category:Arhats]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Buddhist patriarchs]]\n[[Category:5th-century Buddhist monks]]\n", "name_user": "Farang Rak Tham", "label": "safe", "comment": "reordering refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mah%C4%81k%C4%81%C5%9Byapa"}
{"title_page": "Stapleford Abbotts", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country                   = England\n|coordinates               = {{coord|51.638|0.164|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name             = Stapleford Abbotts\n|civil_parish              = Stapleford Abbotts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staplefordabbotts.blogspot.com/|title=Stapleford Abbotts Parish Council|first=Stapleford|last=Abbotts|date=|website=staplefordabbotts.blogspot.com|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n|population                = 959\n|population_ref            = (2001)<br>  1,008  (2001)<ref name=ONS/>\n|shire_district            = [[Epping Forest (district)|Epping Forest]]\n|shire_county              = [[Essex]]\n|region                    = East of England\n|constituency_westminster  = [[Brentwood and Ongar (UK Parliament constituency)|Brentwood and Ongar]]\n|post_town                 = ROMFORD\n|postcode_district         = RM4\n|postcode_area             = RM\n|dial_code                 = [[01708]]\n|os_grid_reference         = TQ505955\n|static_image_name         = St. Mary; the parish church of Stapleford Abbotts - geograph.org.uk - 819650.jpg\n|static_image_caption      = Church of St Mary<br>[[listed building|Grade II architecturally listed]]\n|static_image_2_name       = Tysea Hill, Stapleford Abbots, Essex - geograph.org.uk - 25955.jpg\n|static_image_2_caption    = Tysea Hill, Stapleford Abbots\n|london_distance_mi        = 16.2\n|london_direction          = SW\n|area_total_km2            = 9.57\n}}\n'''Stapleford Abbotts''' is a village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Epping Forest (district)|Epping Forest]] district of [[Essex]], approximately {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} SW of [[Chipping Ongar|Ongar]], {{convert|7|km|mi|abbr=on}} N of [[Romford]] and {{convert|8|km|mi|abbr=on}} SSE of [[Epping, Essex|Epping]]. The whole parish is within the [[M25 motorway]]. The village covers 957 hectares and had a population of 959 in 2001,<ref>[http://www.eppingforestdc.gov.uk/Council_Services/planning/census/StaplefordAbbotts.asp Epping Forest District Council \u2013 Stapleford Abbotts Parish Profile] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041126085941/http://www.eppingforestdc.gov.uk/Council_Services/planning/census/StaplefordAbbotts.asp |date=26 November 2004 }}</ref> increasing to 1,008 at the 2011 Census.<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11129011&c=Stapleford+Abbotts&d=16&e=62&g=6424961&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1473240064312&enc=1 |title=Civil Parish population 2011 |access-date=7 September 2016 |publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe name of the parish arose because the principal manor was held by the [[Bury St. Edmunds Abbey|Abbey of Bury St Edmunds]] from before the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman Conquest]] to the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|Dissolution]]. A story is recorded in the abbey's registers that the lord of the manor was miraculously cured of a lingering illness in 1013 by the body of [[Edmund the Martyr|St Edmund]] as it passed back to Bury Abbey from [[London]]. In gratitude for being cured, he gave the manor to the abbey, either then or some time later.<ref name=bh>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=15673 ''British History'' \u2014 Access to historic documents and research from the [[University of Portsmouth]] and History of Parliament Trust]. A History of the County of Essex: Volume 4: Ongar Hundred (1956), pp. 223\u201328, ''Stapleford Abbots: Manors''. Accessed: 7 September 2007</ref>\n\nThe population rose from 320 in 1801 to 507 in 1831, then fluctuated within that range until 1921 when it was 391. In the 20th century there was a gradual increase in population due to new building in the area from the 1930s onwards. In 1951 the population was 731.<ref name=\"Date accessed: 07 September 2007\"/>\n\nHistorically Stapleford Abbotts was included in the [[hundred (division)|hundred]] of [[Ongar (hundred)|Ongar]]. It formed part of the [[Ongar Rural District]] Council from 1894 until that authority was absorbed into [[Epping and Ongar Rural District]] Council in 1955. Since the local-government reorganisation of 1974 it has been part of Epping Forest District. The present civil parish retains largely the same boundaries as the parish of the mid-19th century.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[civil parishes in England|parish]] is mostly rural and agricultural with a scattering of farms and cottages, much of it is [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] protected land. The northern boundary of the parish is formed by the [[River Roding]]. The remainder of the parish is crossed by streams that feed into it or form the headwater of the [[River Rom]]. The terrain is hilly and 28\u201390 m (92\u2013295 ft) above sea level ([[Above Ordnance Datum|AOD]]) with most between 35 and 80 m (115 and 262 ft).<ref name=os/>\n\nThe village itself is a straggle of mostly 20th-century housing stretching for about a mile along the elevated [[Romford]] to [[Chipping Ongar|Ongar]] road from the boundary with [[Havering-atte-Bower]]. The medieval church (largely rebuilt in the 19th century) is situated in a relatively isolated position a further mile away from what is now the village, reflecting the fact that it had no single nucleus until the 20th century.<ref name=\"Date accessed: 07 September 2007\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=15672 ''British History]. A History of the County of Essex: Volume 4: Ongar Hundred (1956), pp. 222\u201323, ''Stapleford Abbots: Introduction''. Date accessed: 7 September 2007</ref><ref>St Mary's Church \u2014 Grade II listing {{NHLE|num=1165922|access-date=30 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nApart from the village of Stapleford Abbotts, the parish includes the hamlets of Bournebridge, Nuper's Hatch and a small part of [[Passingford Bridge]]. Two places use the village's name outside of it: Stapleford Flight Centre which provides sightseeing flights and Stapleford Abbotts Golf Course (see below).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flysfc.com/ |title=Stapleford Flight Centre, London England |author= |date= |website=www.flysfc.com |access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Nearest Notable Settlements'''\n|Centre    = Stapleford Abbotts\n|North     = [[Stapleford Tawney]]\n|Northeast = <small>''across part of Navestock''</small><br>[[Kelvedon Hatch]]\n|East      = [[Navestock]]\n|Southeast = [[Harold Hill]]\n|South     = [[Havering-atte-Bower]] \n|Southwest = <small>''across Havering Park and Hainault Forest''</small><br>[[Hainault, London|Hainault]]\n|West      = [[Lambourne]]\n|Northwest = [[Theydon Mount]]\n}}\n\n==Localities==\n===Bournebridge===\nAdjoining a farm on the main street to the south is the Bournebridge hamlet. The actual Bourne Bridge crosses the [[Bourne Brook]], which later becomes the [[River Rom]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.az.co.uk/essex-a-z-street-atlas-spiral.html |title=Essex A-Z Street Atlas (spiral) |author= |date= |website=www.az.co.uk |access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> The one Grade II [[listed building]] in the hamlet is the Old The School House.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1165920 |accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> Otherwise it consists of fewer than 20 homes and farms.<ref name=os>{{cite web |url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/shop/os-maps-online.html |title=OS Maps - online and App mapping system - Ordnance Survey Shop |author= |date= |website=www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk |access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Nuper's Hatch===\nThis hamlet ranges in altitude from 60 to 82 m (197 to 296 ft) compared to the village centre's 55 m (180 ft) average. It consists of at least 60 properties centred on Nuper's and Lyng's Farm, in particular the neighbourhood and linear development of '''Tysea Hill'''. On the Tysea Hill ridge is Stapleford Abbotts Golf Course, which is across an almost straight north-south divide in the [[Borough of Brentwood]].<ref name=os/> Six other farms adjoin the main road here, using a hilly [[terrain]]. Curtismill Green itself is in the parish, along with a few cottages, including the grade II listed Honeysuckle Cottage.<ref>Honeysuckle Cottage \u2014 Grade II listing{{NHLE|num=1165956|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> However, most of the hamlet is in [[Navestock]].\n\n==Transport==\nBuses are limited in the area, served by the single Route 375. Route 575 also passes through the area, but offers only one return journey per day.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Route Number\n! Route\n! Via\n! Operator\n! Operational details\n|-\n|'''375''' {{access icon|15px}}\n|[[Abridge|Passingford Bridge]] to [[Romford railway station|Romford Station]] {{Rail-interchange|gb|rail}}.\n|[[Havering-atte-Bower]], [[Collier Row]].\n|[[Arriva Southend]] .\n|Mon-Sat every 90 minutes. [[London Buses]] service. Times<ref>[http://www.londonbusroutes.net/times/375.htm Times]</ref>\n|-\n|'''575''' {{access icon|15px}}\n|[[Epping, Essex|Epping ''High Street'']] to [[Lakeside shopping centre|Lakeside ''Shopping Centre'']].\n|[[Debden, Epping Forest|Debden]], [[Abridge]], [[Havering-atte-Bower]], [[Collier Row]], [[Romford]] {{Rail-interchange|gb|rail}}\n|[[Blue Triangle]]\n|Mon-Fri 1 return journey. [http://www.busmap.org/tt4/575.pdf Times]\n|}\n\nSee [[List of bus routes in London|London Bus Routes]] and [[List of bus routes in Essex|Essex Bus Routes]].\n\nThe nearest railway station is at [[Romford]]. There are frequent mainline services from [[Romford railway station|its station]] to [[London]] and [[East Anglia]]. Both routes 375 and 575 can be used to reach the station.\n\n==Notes and references==\n;Notes \n{{Reflist|group=n}}  \n;References\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Epping Forest}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Essex]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Essex]]\n[[Category:Epping Forest District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country                   = England\n|coordinates               = {{coord|51.638|0.164|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name             = Stapleford Abbotts\n|civil_parish              = Stapleford Abbotts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staplefordabbotts.blogspot.com/|title=Stapleford Abbotts Parish Council|first=Stapleford|last=Abbotts|date=|website=staplefordabbotts.blogspot.com|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n|population                = 959\n|population_ref            = (2001)<br>  1,008  (2001)<ref name=ONS/>\n|shire_district            = [[Epping Forest (district)|Epping Forest]]\n|shire_county              = [[Essex]]\n|region                    = East of England\n|constituency_westminster  = [[Brentwood and Ongar (UK Parliament constituency)|Brentwood and Ongar]]\n|post_town                 = ROMFORD\n|postcode_district         = RM4\n|postcode_area             = RM\n|dial_code                 = [[01708]]\n|os_grid_reference         = TQ505955\n|static_image_name         = St. Mary; the parish church of Stapleford Abbotts - geograph.org.uk - 819650.jpg\n|static_image_caption      = Church of St Mary<br>[[listed building|Grade II architecturally listed]]\n|static_image_2_name       = Tysea Hill, Stapleford Abbots, Essex - geograph.org.uk - 25955.jpg\n|static_image_2_caption    = Tysea Hill, Stapleford Abbots\n|london_distance_mi        = 16.2\n|london_direction          = SW\n|area_total_km2            = 9.57\n}}\n'''Stapleford Abbotts''' is a village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Epping Forest (district)|Epping Forest]] district of [[Essex]], approximately {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} SW of [[Chipping Ongar|Ongar]], {{convert|7|km|mi|abbr=on}} N of [[Romford]] and {{convert|8|km|mi|abbr=on}} SSE of [[Epping, Essex|Epping]]. The whole parish is within the [[M25 motorway]]. The village covers 957 hectares and had a population of 959 in 2001,<ref>[http://www.eppingforestdc.gov.uk/Council_Services/planning/census/StaplefordAbbotts.asp Epping Forest District Council \u2013 Stapleford Abbotts Parish Profile] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041126085941/http://www.eppingforestdc.gov.uk/Council_Services/planning/census/StaplefordAbbotts.asp |date=26 November 2004 }}</ref> increasing to 1,008 at the 2011 Census.<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11129011&c=Stapleford+Abbotts&d=16&e=62&g=6424961&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1473240064312&enc=1 |title=Civil Parish population 2011 |access-date=7 September 2016 |publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe name of the parish arose because the principal manor was held by the [[Bury St. Edmunds Abbey|Abbey of Bury St Edmunds]] from before the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman Conquest]] to the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|Dissolution]]. A story is recorded in the abbey's registers that the lord of the manor was miraculously cured of a lingering illness in 1013 by the body of [[Edmund the Martyr|St Edmund]] as it passed back to Bury Abbey from [[London]]. In gratitude for being cured, he gave the manor to the abbey, either then or some time later.<ref name=bh>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=15673 ''British History'' \u2014 Access to historic documents and research from the [[University of Portsmouth]] and History of Parliament Trust]. A History of the County of Essex: Volume 4: Ongar Hundred (1956), pp. 223\u201328, ''Stapleford Abbots: Manors''. Accessed: 7 September 2007</ref>\n\nThe population rose from 320 in 1801 to 507 in 1831, then fluctuated within that range until 1921 when it was 391. In the 20th century there was a gradual increase in population due to new building in the area from the 1930s onwards. In 1951 the population was 731.<ref name=\"Date accessed: 07 September 2007\"/>\n\nHistorically Stapleford Abbotts was included in the [[hundred (division)|hundred]] of [[Ongar (hundred)|Ongar]]. It formed part of the [[Ongar Rural District]] Council from 1894 until that authority was absorbed into [[Epping and Ongar Rural District]] Council in 1955. Since the local-government reorganisation of 1974 it has been part of Epping Forest District. The present civil parish retains largely the same boundaries as the parish of the mid-19th century.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[civil parishes in England|parish]] is mostly rural and agricultural with a scattering of farms and cottages, much of it is [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] protected land. The northern boundary of the parish is formed by the [[River Roding]]. The remainder of the parish is crossed by streams that feed into it or form the headwater of the [[River Rom]]. The terrain is hilly and 28\u201390 m (92\u2013295 ft) above sea level ([[Above Ordnance Datum|AOD]]) with most between 35 and 80 m (115 and 262 ft).<ref name=os/>\n\nThe village itself is a straggle of mostly 20th-century housing stretching for about a mile along the elevated [[Romford]] to [[Chipping Ongar|Ongar]] road from the boundary with [[Havering-atte-Bower]]. The medieval church (largely rebuilt in the 19th century) is situated in a relatively isolated position a further mile away from what is now the village, reflecting the fact that it had no single nucleus until the 20th century.<ref name=\"Date accessed: 07 September 2007\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=15672 ''British History]. A History of the County of Essex: Volume 4: Ongar Hundred (1956), pp. 222\u201323, ''Stapleford Abbots: Introduction''. Date accessed: 7 September 2007</ref><ref>St Mary's Church \u2014 Grade II listing {{NHLE|num=1165922|access-date=30 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nApart from the village of Stapleford Abbotts, the parish includes the hamlets of Bournebridge, Nuper's Hatch and a small part of [[Passingford Bridge]]. Two places use the village's name outside of it: Stapleford Flight Centre which provides sightseeing flights and Stapleford Abbotts Golf Course (see below).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flysfc.com/ |title=Stapleford Flight Centre, London England |author= |date= |website=www.flysfc.com |access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Nearest Notable Settlements'''\n|Centre    = Stapleford Abbotts\n|North     = [[Stapleford Tawney]]\n|Northeast = <small>''across part of Navestock''</small><br>[[Kelvedon Hatch]]\n|East      = [[Navestock]]\n|Southeast = [[Harold Hill]]\n|South     = [[Havering-atte-Bower]] \n|Southwest = <small>''across Havering Park and Hainault Forest''</small><br>[[Hainault, London|Hainault]]\n|West      = [[Lambourne]]\n|Northwest = [[Theydon Mount]]\n}}\n\n==Localities==\n===Bournebridge===\nAdjoining a farm on the main street to the south is the Bournebridge hamlet. The actual Bourne Bridge crosses the [[Bourne Brook]], which later becomes the [[River Rom]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.az.co.uk/essex-a-z-street-atlas-spiral.html |title=Essex A-Z Street Atlas (spiral) |author= |date= |website=www.az.co.uk |access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> The one Grade II [[listed building]] in the hamlet is the Old The School House.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1165920 |accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> Otherwise it consists of fewer than 20 homes and farms.<ref name=os>{{cite web |url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/shop/os-maps-online.html |title=OS Maps - online and App mapping system - Ordnance Survey Shop |author= |date= |website=www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk |access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Nuper's Hatch===\nThis hamlet ranges in altitude from 60 to 82 m (197 to 296 ft) compared to the village centre's 55 m (180 ft) average. It consists of at least 60 properties centred on Nuper's and Lyng's Farm, in particular the neighbourhood and linear development of '''Tysea Hill'''. On the Tysea Hill ridge is Stapleford Abbotts Golf Course, which is across an almost straight north-south divide in the [[Borough of Brentwood]].<ref name=os/> Six other farms adjoin the main road here, using a hilly [[terrain]]. Curtismill Green itself is in the parish, along with a few cottages, including the grade II listed Honeysuckle Cottage.<ref>Honeysuckle Cottage \u2014 Grade II listing{{NHLE|num=1165956|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> However, most of the hamlet is in [[Navestock]].\n\n==Transport==\nBuses are limited in the area, served by the single Route 375. Route 575 also passes through the area, but offers only one return journey per day.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Route Number\n! Route\n! Via\n! Operator\n! Operational details\n|-\n|'''375''' {{access icon|15px}}\n|[[Abridge|Passingford Bridge]] to [[Romford railway station|Romford Station]] {{Rail-interchange|gb|rail}}.\n|[[Havering-atte-Bower]], [[Collier Row]].\n|[[Arriva Southend]] .\n|Mon-Sat every 90 minutes. [[London Buses]] service. Times<ref>[http://www.londonbusroutes.net/times/375.htm Times]</ref>\n|-\n|'''575''' {{access icon|15px}}\n|[[Epping, Essex|Epping ''High Street'']] to [[Lakeside shopping centre|Lakeside ''Shopping Centre'']].\n|[[Debden, Epping Forest|Debden]], [[Abridge]], [[Havering-atte-Bower]], [[Collier Row]], [[Romford]] {{Rail-interchange|gb|rail}}\n|[[Blue Triangle]]\n|Mon-Fri 1 return journey. [http://www.busmap.org/tt4/575.pdf Times]\n|}\n\nSee [[List of bus routes in London|London Bus Routes]] and [[List of bus routes in Essex|Essex Bus Routes]].\n\nThe nearest railway station is at [[Romford]]. There are frequent mainline services from [[Romford railway station|its station]] to [[London]] and [[East Anglia]]. Both routes 375 and 575 can be used to reach the station.\n\n==Notes and references==\n;Notes \n{{Reflist|group=n}}  \n;References\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Epping Forest}}\n\n[[Category:Epping Forest District]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Essex]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Category:Villages in Essex", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stapleford_Abbotts"}
