{"title_page": "She Who Must Be Obeyed (sculpture)", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file =She Who Must Be Obeyed tony smith 006.JPG\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 250px\n| title              = She Who Must Be Obeyed\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = [[Tony Smith (sculptor)|Tony Smith]]\n| year               = {{Start date|1975}}\n| type               = [[Steel]], painted blue\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 30  \n| width_imperial     = 8\n| length_imperial    = 24\n| metric_unit        = m\n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|38.8946|-77.0157}}\n| owner              = [[General Services Administration]]\n}}\n\n'''''She Who Must Be Obeyed''''' is a [[minimalism|minimalist]] sculpture 33 feet wide and 16 feet deep made by [[Tony Smith (sculptor)|Tony Smith]] in 1975.<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=13592H83E0B21.1948&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!5134~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=she+who+must+be+obeyed&index=.GW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 \"She Who Must Be Obeyed, (sculpture).\"]. ''SIRIS''</ref> It is located at the [[Frances Perkins Building]], in [[downtown, Washington, D.C.]]. The piece consists of nine geometric [[rhomboid]] units, bolted and welded together and painted blue.\n\nTony Smith's career encompassed architecture, painting, and sculpture. The [[General Services Administration]] commissioned the 21-foot-high steel construction that is painted blue in 1974 for its Art in Public Places program. Smith said that he was willing to forgo the standard honorarium for the sculpture. \"I felt very honored to do something in the national capital...As far as I was concerned, I would be perfectly willing to supply it at cost\u2026.it\u2019s right near the Capitol, and it\u2019s a very nice place to be.\"<ref name=Thalacker>{{cite book|title=The Place of Art in the World of Architecture|year=1980|publisher=Chelsea House Publications|isbn=0877540985|page=184|editor=Donald W. Thalacker}}</ref> \nThe $98,000 fee he was awarded was consumed by the production of the imposing work.<ref name=Thalacker />\n\n==Description==\nDuring the spring of 1976 ''She Who Must Be Obeyed'' was installed on the east plaza of the newly constructed Department of Labor building\u2014subsequently named the Frances Perkins Building\u2014in Washington, D.C., not far from the east wing of the [[National Gallery of Art]].\n\nUsing the jargon of a [[Master builder (occupation)|master builder]], which he had been, Smith explained that his sculpture \u201cis the cross-section of a space frame made up of tetrahedral and octahedral. It\u2019s called simply a rhombus.\u201d<ref name=Thalacker />\n\nFor various reasons ''She'' never became one of the artist's better-known sculptures.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tuchman|first=Phyllis|title=Tony Smith, A Modern Master|journal=New Jersey Monthly|date=January 1981|pages=124}}</ref> One possible reason:  until 2009 it was not easy to see ''She.''  The work was placed in an outdoor corner of the t-shaped Frances Perkins Building near Second Street NW, set back\u2014and difficult to see\u2014from the street.  Access to the work was made easier after it was restored in 2008\u20132009, and reinstalled on the other side of the Perkins Building, on a grassy plaza close to the intersection of Third and C Streets NW.\n\nThe construction is also an anomaly in the artist's career: instead of being painted black like most of Smith's other works, or even yellow, like a select few, it is bright blue.  Initially, the artist had wanted ''She'' to be the color of [[pool cue]] chalk.<ref name=Thalacker />   In comparison to the artworks published in the pages of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] catalogue that accompanied the retrospective curated by Robert Storr in 1998, it is reproduced in black and white, not color.<ref name=Storr>{{cite book|title=Tony Smith: Architect Painter Sculptor|year=1998|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|isbn=0-87070-071-5|pages=175|editor1-first=Robert|editor1-last=Storr}}</ref>\n\nBecause Tony Smith's early structures, works like ''Die'' and ''The Elevens Are Up'', were monochromatic, smooth-surfaced, and straight-edged, the older artist was referred to, during this phase of his career, as a Minimalist. His closest friends and colleagues, however, included Abstract Expressionists [[Jackson Pollock]] and [[Barnett Newman]]. His work straddles both genres.\n\n==Title==\nSmith had an open-ended approach to titling his works. Some shapes reminded him of specific objects; others carry the names and initials of dear friends. With its horn-like appendages, ''Moses'' refers to [[Moses (Michelangelo)|Michelangelo's portrayal of that patriarch]]. Because he was well read, and even had run a secondhand bookstore during the [[Great Depression]], a number of the artist's sculptures have literary monikers.<ref name=Storr /> ''[[Gracehoper (2/3)|Gracehoper]]'', for example, is a word that appears in ''[[Finnegans Wake]]'', [[James Joyce]]'s Modernist classic. ''She Who Must Be Obeyed'' derives from a more populist source, the 1886\u201387 novel ''[[She: A History of Adventure]]'' by [[H. Rider Haggard]], a tale of a lost kingdom.\n\n==See also== \n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n* [[List of Tony Smith sculptures]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web| author=dcMemorials | year=2006 | title=''She Who Must be Obeyed'' sculpture in Washington, D.C. | work= | publisher=dcMemorials| url=http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0000343.htm | accessdate= June 8, 2010}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://eyelevel.si.edu/2007/06/in_this_case_to.html|title=In This Case: Tony Smith|date=June 5, 2007|publisher=Smithsonian American Art Museum}}\n\n{{Tony Smith}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:She Who Must Be Obeyed (sculpture)}}\n[[Category:1975 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures by Tony Smith]]\n[[Category:Steel sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file =She Who Must Be Obeyed tony smith 006.JPG\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 250px\n| title              = She Who Must Be Obeyed\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = [[Tony Smith (sculptor)|Tony Smith]]\n| year               = {{Start date|1975}}\n| type               = [[Steel]], painted blue\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 30  \n| width_imperial     = 8\n| length_imperial    = 24\n| metric_unit        = m\n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|38.8946|-77.0157}}\n| owner              = [[General Services Administration]]\n}}\n\n'''''She Who Must Be Obeyed''''' is a [[minimalism|minimalist]] sculpture 33 feet wide and 16 feet deep made by [[Tony Smith (sculptor)|Tony Smith]] in 1975.<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=13592H83E0B21.1948&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!5134~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=she+who+must+be+obeyed&index=.GW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 \"She Who Must Be Obeyed, (sculpture).\"]. ''SIRIS''</ref> It is located at the [[Frances Perkins Building]], in [[downtown, Washington, D.C.]]. The piece consists of nine geometric [[rhomboid]] units, bolted and welded together and painted blue.\n\nTony Smith's career encompassed architecture, painting, and sculpture. The [[General Services Administration]] commissioned the 21-foot-high steel construction that is painted blue in 1974 for its Art in Public Places program. Smith said that he was willing to forgo the standard honorarium for the sculpture. \"I felt very honored to do something in the national capital...As far as I was concerned, I would be perfectly willing to supply it at cost\u2026.it\u2019s right near the Capitol, and it\u2019s a very nice place to be.\"<ref name=Thalacker>{{cite book|title=The Place of Art in the World of Architecture|year=1980|publisher=Chelsea House Publications|isbn=0877540985|page=184|editor=Donald W. Thalacker}}</ref> \nThe $98,000 fee he was awarded was consumed by the production of the imposing work.<ref name=Thalacker />\n\n==Description==\nDuring the spring of 1976 ''She Who Must Be Obeyed'' was installed on the east plaza of the newly constructed Department of Labor building\u2014subsequently named the Frances Perkins Building\u2014in Washington, D.C., not far from the east wing of the [[National Gallery of Art]].\n\nUsing the jargon of a [[Master builder (occupation)|master builder]], which he had been, Smith explained that his sculpture \u201cis the cross-section of a space frame made up of tetrahedral and octahedral. It\u2019s called simply a rhombus.\u201d<ref name=Thalacker />\n\nFor various reasons ''She'' never became one of the artist's better-known sculptures.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tuchman|first=Phyllis|title=Tony Smith, A Modern Master|journal=New Jersey Monthly|date=January 1981|pages=124}}</ref> One possible reason:  until 2009 it was not easy to see ''She.''  The work was placed in an outdoor corner of the t-shaped Frances Perkins Building near Second Street NW, set back\u2014and difficult to see\u2014from the street.  Access to the work was made easier after it was restored in 2008\u20132009, and reinstalled on the other side of the Perkins Building, on a grassy plaza close to the intersection of Third and C Streets NW.\n\nThe construction is also an anomaly in the artist's career: instead of being painted black like most of Smith's other works, or even yellow, like a select few, it is bright blue.  Initially, the artist had wanted ''She'' to be the color of [[pool cue]] chalk.<ref name=Thalacker />   In comparison to the artworks published in the pages of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] catalogue that accompanied the retrospective curated by Robert Storr in 1998, it is reproduced in black and white, not color.<ref name=Storr>{{cite book|title=Tony Smith: Architect Painter Sculptor|year=1998|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|isbn=0-87070-071-5|pages=175|editor1-first=Robert|editor1-last=Storr}}</ref>\n\nBecause Tony Smith's early structures, works like ''Die'' and ''The Elevens Are Up'', were monochromatic, smooth-surfaced, and straight-edged, the older artist was referred to, during this phase of his career, as a Minimalist. His closest friends and colleagues, however, included Abstract Expressionists [[Jackson Pollock]] and [[Barnett Newman]]. His work straddles both genres.\n\n==Title==\nSmith had an open-ended approach to titling his art. Some shapes reminded him of specific objects; others carry the names and initials of dear friends. With its horn-like appendages, ''Moses'' refers to [[Moses (Michelangelo)|Michelangelo's version of the patriarch]]. Because he was well read, and even had run a secondhand bookstore during the Depression, a number of the artist's sculptures have literary monikers.<ref name=Storr /> ''[[Gracehoper (2/3)|Gracehoper]]'', for example, appears in ''[[Finnegans Wake]]'', [[James Joyce]]\u2019s Modernist classic. ''She Who Must Be Obeyed'' derives from a more populist source, the 1886\u20131887 novel ''[[She: A History of Adventure]]'' by [[H. Rider Haggard]], a tale of a lost kingdom.\n\n==See also== \n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n* [[List of Tony Smith sculptures]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n