{"title_page": "Mikulov", "text_new": "{{redirect|Nikolsburg|the [[Hasidic dynasty]]|Nikolsburg (Hasidic dynasty)}}\n{{for|the municipality in the [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]]|Mikulov (Teplice District)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mikulov\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Mikulov pohled 2.jpg\n| image_caption           = Old town centre and castle\n| image_flag              = Flag of Mikulov, B\u0159eclav District, Czech Republic.svg\n| image_shield            = Mikulov_znak.png\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Czech Republic\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[South Moravian Region|South Moravian]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[B\u0159eclav District|B\u0159eclav]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Czech Republic\n| pushpin_relief          = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Czech Republic\n| coordinates             = {{coord|48|48|20|N|16|38|16|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = Rostislav Ko\u0161tial\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = City rights\n| established_date        = 1410\n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 45.34\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 242\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2019-01-01<ref>{{cite web |title=Population of municipalities of the Czech republic|url=https://www.czso.cz/documents/10180/91917344/1300721903.pdf/ea01e710-2ae5-49f3-8792-ebb384754346?version=1.0|publisher=Czech Statistical Office|accessdate=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 7359\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 692 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [http://www.mikulov.cz/ www.mikulov.cz]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Mikulov''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8m\u026akulof}}; {{lang-de|Nikolsburg}}; {{lang-yi|\u05e0\u05d9\u05e7\u05d0\u05dc\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d2}}, ''Nikolshburg'') is a town in the [[South Moravian Region]] of the [[Czech Republic]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe town is part of the historic [[Moravia]] region, located directly on the border with [[Lower Austria]]. In the south, a road border crossing leads to the neighbouring Austrian municipality of [[Drasenhofen]]. The highway is part of the [[European route E461]] and is to be extended as the [[R52 expressway (Czech Republic)|R52 expressway]].\n\nMikulov is situated between the Pavlovsk\u00e9 vrchy hilly area and the edge of the [[Mikulov Highlands]], stretching up to the [[Thaya]] river and the three [[Nov\u00e9 Ml\u00fdny reservoirs]]. The [[P\u00e1lava Protected Landscape Area]] begins in Mikulov, and so does the [[Moravian Karst]].\n\n==History==\nAfter the [[Margraviate of Moravia]] was established, the settlement of ''Nikulsburch'' was first mentioned in a 1249 deed, issued by the [[P\u0159emyslid dynasty|P\u0159emyslid]] margrave [[Ottokar II of Bohemia|Ottokar II]] who granted it, including a castle, and the surrounding area to the [[Duchy of Austria|Austrian]] noble Henry I of [[Princely Family of Liechtenstein|Liechtenstein]]. In 1262 the possession was confirmed by Ottokar, [[List of Bohemian monarchs|Bohemian king]] since 1253. After King [[Rudolf I of Germany]] had defeated Ottokar at the 1278 [[Battle on the Marchfeld]], he then vested Henry II of Liechtenstein with [[market rights]] ''in villa Nicolspurch''. [[German Bohemians|German]] citizens were called in and lived there until their [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|expulsion]] in 1945 according to the [[Bene\u0161 decrees]].\n\n===Bohemian Crown===\nIn 1526, the [[Anabaptists|Anabaptist]] leader [[Balthasar Hubmaier]] came from [[Old Swiss Confederacy|Switzerland]] to Nikolsburg, where he was captured and arrested by the forces of the [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]] king [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] in the following year. The town remained in the Liechtenstein family until 1560, and in 1572 Emperor [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian II]] granted the fief to his ambassador to the Spanish court Adam von [[Dietrichstein]]. From 1575 until the 20th century, Nikolsburg remained the proprietary possession of the Dietrichstein noble family and its [[Mensdorff-Pouilly]] successors.\n\nIn 1621, during the [[Thirty Years' War]], Cardinal [[Franz von Dietrichstein]] signed the [[Peace of Nikolsburg|Treaty of Nikolsburg]] with the Transylvanian prince [[Gabriel Bethlen]] at [[Mikulov Castle]]. Four years later, Emperor [[Ferdinand II, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand II]] and his [[Aulic titulature|aulic]] council met at the castle, where General [[Albrecht von Wallenstein]] received his commission and was elevated to a [[Duchy of Friedland|Duke of Friedland]]. Franz von Dietrichstein also established the first [[Piarists|Piarist]] college north of the Alps in Nikolsburg.\n\nAfter a fire damaged the original Nikolsburg Castle in 1719, the Dietrichstein family reconstructed the ch\u00e2teau to its present appearance. After the [[Austro-Prussian War]], Count [[Alajos K\u00e1rolyi]] began work on a peace treaty in Nikolsburg that led to the [[Treaty of Prague (1866)|Treaty of Prague]] in 1866.\n\n===Jewish Mikulov===\n:{{See also|Familianten}}\n[[File:V09p305001 Nikolsburg.jpg|260px|thumb|Jewish quarter (1900s)]]\n\nThe beginning of the Jewish settlement in Nikolsburg dates as far as 1421, when Jews were expelled from [[Vienna]] and the neighboring province of [[Lower Austria]] by the duke of Austria, [[Albert II of Germany]]. The refugees settled in the town situated close to the Austrian border, some {{convert|85|km|0|abbr=off}} from the [[Austria]]n capital, under the protection of the princes of Liechtenstein, and additional settlers were brought after the expulsions of the Jews from the Moravian royal boroughs by the king [[Ladislaus the Posthumous]] after 1454.<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\">Nezhodov\u00e1, So\u0148a. ''The Jewish Mikulov'' (\u017didovsk\u00fd Mikulov). 1. ed. Brno: Matice moravsk\u00e1, 2006, 423 p. {{ISBN|80-86488-28-4}}</ref>\n\nThe settlement grew in importance and in the first half of the 16th century Nikolsburg became the seat of the regional [[rabbi]] of [[Moravia]], thus becoming a cultural centre of Moravian Jewry. The famous rabbi [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel]] (1525 &ndash; 1609), who is said to have created the [[golem]] of [[Prague]], officiated here for twenty years as the second regional rabbi between 1553 and 1573.<ref>[http://travel.nytimes.com/2011/09/25/travel/in-the-czech-republic-moravia-and-its-castles.html?pagewanted=all Moravia and its castles]</ref> Cardinal [[Franz von Dietrichstein]], son of Adam von Dietrichstein, was a special protector of the Jews, whose taxes were necessary to finance the Thirty Years' War.<ref name=\"Jewish Encycl\">Jewish Encyclopedia, ''\"[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?letter=N&artid=292 Jewish Nikolsburg]\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref>\n\nIn the first half of the 18th century, the congregation in Nikolsburg totalled over 600 families, being the largest Jewish settlement in [[Moravia]]. The census of 1754 decreed by Empress [[Maria Theresa of Austria]] ascertained that there were some 620 families established in Nikolsburg, i.e. the Jewish population of about 3,000 comprised half of the town's inhabitants.<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\"/> Only a small number of Jews could make their living in the town as artisans; the rest had to become merchants. The congregation suffered severely during the [[Silesian wars]] (1740&ndash;1742, 1744&ndash;1745 and 1756&ndash;1763), when they had to furnish the monarchy with their share in the supertaxes exacted by the government of Maria Theresa from the Jews of Moravia.<ref name=\"Jewish Encycl\"/>\n\nQuite a number of Nikolsburg Jews continued to earn their livelihood in Vienna, where they were permitted to stay for some time on special passports. The freedom of residence, which was conceded to the Jews in Austria in 1848, reduced the number of resident Jews in Nikolsburg to less than one-third of the population which it contained at the time of its highest development. In 1904, there were 749 Jewish residents in the city, out of a total population of 8,192.<ref name=\"Jewish Encycl\"/> In 1938, prior to the [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia]], the city population totaled about 8,000 mostly German-speaking inhabitants. Out of these, 472 were Jewish at this time.<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\"/> The Jewish settlement in Nikolsburg ceased to exist during World War II, as only 110 managed to emigrate in time, and 327 of Mikulov's Jews did not survive the [[the Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\"/> On April 15th, 1945 21 Hungarian Jewish prisoners working in a clay pit were massacred.<ref>http://www.mikulov.cz/tourism/monuments-and-sights/monuments-of-jewish-community/jewish-cemetery/more-information/</ref>\n\nFollowing World War II, the town's German population was brutally expelled in 1945-46 by the Czechoslovak government. In 1948, Mikulov's population was around 5,200.\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Mikulov 4826.jpg|260px|thumb|St. Sebastian Chapel on the Holy Hill (''Svat\u00fd Kope\u010dek'')]]\n[[File:Mikulov-Nicolsburg city seal.jpg|thumb|260px|upright|Mikulov (Nicolsburg) official seal, 1810]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" <hiddentext>generated with [[:de:Wikipedia:Helferlein/VBA-Macro for EXCEL tableconversion]] V1.7<\\hiddentext>\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|width=\"64\" height=\"14\"|Census year\n|width=\"60\" rowspan=\"2\"|Population\n|width=\"260\" colspan=\"3\"|Ethnicity of inhabitants\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"14\"|year\n|German\n|Czechs\n|other\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1793\n|7440\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1836\n|8421\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1869\n|7173\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1880\n|7642\n|7447\n|144\n|61\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1890\n|8210\n|8057\n|79\n|74\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1900\n|8092\n|7843\n|170\n|79\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1910\n|8043\n|7787\n|189\n|67\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1921\n|7699\n|6359\n|626\n|485\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1930\n|7790\n|6409\n|898\n|483\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"14\"|1939\n|7886\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|}<ref>Historick\u00fd m\u00edstopis Moravy a Slezska v letech 1848\u20131960, sv.9. 1984</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nMikulov is a centre of [[Czech wine|Czech wine-making]] due to its favorable geographic location and climate, as well as its unique history. Mikulov is not only the centre, but the namesake of, the Moravian wine sub-region ''vinarsk\u00e1 podoblast [[Mikulovsk\u00e1 wine|Mikulovsk\u00e1]]''.<ref>Wine of the Czech Republic, ''\"[http://www.wineofczechrepublic.cz/2-1-2-sub-region-mikulov-en.html Mikulov Wine Region] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719024934/http://www.wineofczechrepublic.cz/2-1-2-sub-region-mikulov-en.html |date=2011-07-19 }}\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref> Twelve registered [[cadastral]] vineyard tracts (Czech: ''trat'') are situated within the Mikulov wine village as defined under the Czech Viticulture Act.<ref>Czech Wine Law, ''\"[http://www.vinarskyfond.cz/legislativa/1-vinarska_legislativa_2004.pdf Viticulture Act of 2004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718190125/http://www.vinarskyfond.cz/legislativa/1-vinarska_legislativa_2004.pdf |date=2011-07-18 }}\"'', pg 87-90, Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref> Other significant economic activities in Mikulov are the machine-making and clay industries, as well as oil found at the edge of the [[Viennese Basin]].\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Mikulov, z\u00e1mek.JPG|thumb|260px|[[Mikulov Castle]]]]\nMikulov's historic buildings, such as [[Mikulov Castle]], and the surrounding wine country draw tourists from the Czech Republic and neighboring countries. Beginning in Mikulov, the 65 kilometer long [[Mikulov Wine Trail]] winds throughout the Mikulov wine region and is a part of [[wine tourism]] in the area. Other noteworthy historic sights are the [[Dietrichstein]] sepulchre, the old [[Jewish quarter (diaspora)|Jewish Quarter]], and the [[Piarist]] College. Several historic churches and a synagogue, built in various architectural styles, are located in Mikulov, including the [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] Church of St. V\u00e1clav and charnel house, the [[Baroque]] Church of St. John the Baptist, St. Sebastian Chapel on the Holy Hill (''Svat\u00fd Kope\u010dek''), the [[neo-Gothic]] Eastern Christian Church of St. Nicolas, and the Altschul Synagogue.\n\n==Notable people==\n===Born in Mikulov===\n* [[Johann Ferdinand Hertodt]] (1645\u20131722), German Moravian physician and writer\n* [[Moses ben Avraham Avinu]] (?\u20131733), printer, author, Christian convert to Judaism\n* [[Jakab Fellner|Jakob Fellner]] (1722\u20131780), German Moravian Baroque architect\n* [[Joseph von Sonnenfels]], n\u00e9 Lipmann (1732\u20131817), Austrian and German Jewish (later Christian) jurist, novelist\n* [[Anton Joseph Leeb]] (1769\u20131837), [[Mayor of Vienna]] (1835-1837)\n* [[Heinrich Landesmann]] (1821\u20131902), Austrian Jewish poet and philosophical writer\n* [[Heinrich Auspitz]] (1835\u20131886), Austrian Jewish dermatologist\n* [[Elkan Bauer]] (1852\u20131942), Austrian Jewish composer of popular waltzes\n* [[Edmund Wengraf]] (1860\u20131933, Vienna), Austrian jurist, journalist, narrative writer, novelist, essayist, poet, theatre critic\n* [[Siegfried Altmann]] (1872\u20131961), Austrian Jewish educator and former Director of Das Israelitisches Blindeninstitut, a Jewish institute for blind children.<ref>Center for Jewish History Digital Collections, ''\"[http://digital.cjh.org/R/?func=dbin-jump-full&object_id=431106&local_base=GEN01 Sigfried Altmann Collection]\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref>\n* [[Moriz Jung]] (1885\u20131915), Austrian painter and graphic artist, notable for his work for the [[Wiener Werkst\u00e4tte]]\n* [[Adolf Sch\u00e4rf]] (1890\u20131965), Austrian Social Democratic politician and President of Austria (1957-1965)\n* [[Manfred Ackermann]] (1898\u20131991), Austrian Social Democratic politician\n* [[Karel Krautgartner]] (1922\u20131982), Czech jazz and classical clarinetist, saxophonist, arranger, composer, conductor and teacher\n\n===Resided in Mikulov===\n* [[Balthasar Hubmaier]] (1480\u20131528), Moravian German Anabaptist ([[Schwertler]] [[:de:Schwertler|(de)]]) leader\n* [[Leonhard Schiemer]] (1500\u20131528), Austrian Anabaptist writer\n* [[Adam von Dietrichstein]] (1527\u20131590), purchaser of the Mikulov estate in 1575\n* [[Dietrichstein|Maximilian, Prince of Dietrichstein]] (1596\u20131655), grandson of Adam von Dietrichstein and owner of the Mikulov estate\n* [[Aaron Samuel Kaidanover]] (1614\u20131676), Polish-Lithuanian rabbi\n* [[Joseph Almosnino]] (1642\u20131689), Greek-Serbian rabbi\n* [[Judah he-Hasid (Jerusalem)|Judah he-Hasid]] (1660\u20131700), Jewish preacher\n* [[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin]] (1745\u20131815), Polish rabbi\n* [[Abraham Trebitsch]] (1760\u20131840), Austrian Jewish scholar\n* [[Simcha Bunim of Peshischa]] (1765\u20131827), Polish rabbi\n* [[Bonif\u00e1c Buzek]] (1788\u20131839) [[:de:Bonif\u00e1c Buzek|(de)]], Moravian priest\n* [[Abraham Neuda]] (1812\u20131854), Moravian rabbi\n* [[Simon Bacher]] (1823\u20131891), Hungarian Neo-Hebraic poet\n* [[Meyer Kayserling]] (1829\u20131905), German rabbi\n* [[Samuel Baeck]] (1834\u20131912), German rabbi\n* [[Karl Borrom\u00e4us Landsteiner|Karl (Carl) Borrom\u00e4us Landsteiner]] (''pseudonym: Arthur Landerstein''; 1835, Schlo\u00df Stoitzendorf, [[Stoitzendorf]] bei [[Eggenburg]], Lower Austria - 1909, Mikulov), Austrian [[Catholic theologian]], author<ref>aeiou Encyclopedia, ''\"[http://www.aeiou.at/aeiou.encyclop./l159167.htm;internal&action=_setlanguage.action?LANGUAGE=en Landsteiner, Karl]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref>\n* [[Karl Renner]] (1870\u20131950), Austrian Social Democratic politician, Chancellor of Austria (1918\u20131920, 1945), President of Austria (1945\u20131950)\n* [[Richard Teltscher]] (1888\u20131974), Austrian Jewish wine-merchant, patron and patriot, founder of the [[Jewish Central Museum for Moravia-Silesia]] in Mikulov\n\n===Rabbis===\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Judah L\u00f6w ben Bezaleel]], the first rabbi of Nikolsburg, chief rabbi of Moravia, officiated in Nikolsburg about 1553\u20131573\n* [[Judah L\u00f6b Eilenburg]] (1574\u20131618)\n* Gabriel ben Chajjim ben Sinaj (1618\u20131624)\n* [[Yom-\u1e6cob Lipmann Heller]] (1624\u2013 )\n* [[Pethahiah ben Joseph]] (1631\u20131637)\n* Abraham ben Mordechaj Jaffe (1637\u20131647)\n* [[Menahem Mendel Krochmal]] (1648\u20131661)\n* [[Gershon Ashkenazi]] (1661\u2013 )\n* [[Aaron Jacob ben Ezekiel]] ( \u20131671)\n* [[Judah L\u00f6b, son of Menahem Krochmal]] (1672\u20131684)\n* [[Eliezer Mendel Fanta]] (1684\u20131690)\n* [[David Oppenheim (rabbi)|David Oppenheim]] (1690\u20131702)\n* [[Gabriel Eskeles]] (1709\u20131718)\n* Bernard Eskeles (1718\u20131753)\n* Moses Lwow-Lemburger (1753\u20131757)\n* [[Gershon Politz]] (1757\u20131772)\n* [[Shmelke of Nikolsburg|Shmuel \"S(c)hmelke\" (ben Hirsh Halevi) Horowitz of Nikolsburg]] (1772\u20131778)\n* [[Gershon Chajes]] (1780\u20131789)\n* [[Mordecai Benet]] (1789\u20131829)\n* [[Nahum Trebitsch]] (1831\u20131842)\n* [[Samson Raphael Hirsch]] (1847\u20131851)\n* Hirsch Teltscher (1851\u20131853)\n* Isak Weinberger (1853\u20131855)\n* [[Solomon Quetsch]] (1855\u20131856)\n* [[Mayer Feuchtwang]] (1861\u20131888)\n* [[David Feuchtwang]] (1892\u20131903), also [[IKG Wien|chief rabbi of Vienna]]; Son of Mayer\n* [[Moritz Levin]] (since 1903\u20131918)\n* Alfred Willmann (1919\u20131938)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Czech Republic}}\n\nMikulov is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Partnersk\u00e1 m\u011bsta|url=http://www.mikulov.cz/mesto-mikulov/partnerska-mesta/|publisher=M\u011bsto Mikulov|language=cs|accessdate=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Bardejov]], [[Slovakia]] \n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Galanta]], [[Slovakia]]  \n*[[Katzrin]], [[Israeli settlement]] in the [[Golan Heights]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Laa an der Thaya]], [[Austria]]\n*{{flagicon|CZE}} [[\u0160umperk]], [[Czech Republic]]\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Tuch\u00f3w]], [[Poland]]\n\n