 motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Mikulov pohled 2.jpg\n| image_caption           = Old town centre and castle\n| image_flag              = Flag of Mikulov, B\u0159eclav District, Czech Republic.svg\n| image_shield            = Mikulov_znak.png\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Czech Republic\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[South Moravian Region|South Moravian]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[B\u0159eclav District|B\u0159eclav]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Czech Republic\n| pushpin_relief          = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Czech Republic\n| coordinates             = {{coord|48|48|20|N|16|38|16|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = Rostislav Ko\u0161tial\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = City rights\n| established_date        = 1410\n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 45.34\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 242\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2019-01-01<ref>{{cite web |title=Population of municipalities of the Czech republic|url=https://www.czso.cz/documents/10180/91917344/1300721903.pdf/ea01e710-2ae5-49f3-8792-ebb384754346?version=1.0|publisher=Czech Statistical Office|accessdate=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 7359\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 692 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [http://www.mikulov.cz/ www.mikulov.cz]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Mikulov''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8m\u026akulof}}; {{lang-de|Nikolsburg}}; {{lang-yi|\u05e0\u05d9\u05e7\u05d0\u05dc\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d2}}, ''Nikolshburg'') is a town in the [[South Moravian Region]] of the [[Czech Republic]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe town is part of the historic [[Moravia]] region, located directly on the border with [[Lower Austria]]. In the south, a road border crossing leads to the neighbouring Austrian municipality of [[Drasenhofen]]. The highway is part of the [[European route E461]] and is to be extended as the [[R52 expressway (Czech Republic)|R52 expressway]].\n\nMikulov is situated between the Pavlovsk\u00e9 vrchy hilly area and the edge of the [[Mikulov Highlands]], stretching up to the [[Thaya]] river and the three [[Nov\u00e9 Ml\u00fdny reservoirs]]. The [[P\u00e1lava Protected Landscape Area]] begins in Mikulov, and so does the [[Moravian Karst]].\n\n==History==\nAfter the [[Margraviate of Moravia]] was established, the settlement of ''Nikulsburch'' was first mentioned in a 1249 deed, issued by the [[P\u0159emyslid dynasty|P\u0159emyslid]] margrave [[Ottokar II of Bohemia|Ottokar II]] who granted it, including a castle, and the surrounding area to the [[Duchy of Austria|Austrian]] noble Henry I of [[Princely Family of Liechtenstein|Liechtenstein]]. In 1262 the possession was confirmed by Ottokar, [[List of Bohemian monarchs|Bohemian king]] since 1253. After King [[Rudolf I of Germany]] had defeated Ottokar at the 1278 [[Battle on the Marchfeld]], he then vested Henry II of Liechtenstein with [[market rights]] ''in villa Nicolspurch''. [[German Bohemians|German]] citizens were called in and lived there until their [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|expulsion]] in 1945 according to the [[Bene\u0161 decrees]].\n\n===Bohemian Crown===\nIn 1526, the [[Anabaptists|Anabaptist]] leader [[Balthasar Hubmaier]] came from [[Old Swiss Confederacy|Switzerland]] to Nikolsburg, where he was captured and arrested by the forces of the [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]] king [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] in the following year. The town remained in the Liechtenstein family until 1560, and in 1572 Emperor [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian II]] granted the fief to his ambassador to the Spanish court Adam von [[Dietrichstein]]. From 1575 until the 20th century, Nikolsburg remained the proprietary possession of the Dietrichstein noble family and its [[Mensdorff-Pouilly]] successors.\n\nIn 1621, during the [[Thirty Years' War]], Cardinal [[Franz von Dietrichstein]] signed the [[Peace of Nikolsburg|Treaty of Nikolsburg]] with the Transylvanian prince [[Gabriel Bethlen]] at [[Mikulov Castle]]. Four years later, Emperor [[Ferdinand II, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand II]] and his [[Aulic titulature|aulic]] council met at the castle, where General [[Albrecht von Wallenstein]] received his commission and was elevated to a [[Duchy of Friedland|Duke of Friedland]]. Franz von Dietrichstein also established the first [[Piarists|Piarist]] college north of the Alps in Nikolsburg.\n\nAfter a fire damaged the original Nikolsburg Castle in 1719, the Dietrichstein family reconstructed the ch\u00e2teau to its present appearance. After the [[Austro-Prussian War]], Count [[Alajos K\u00e1rolyi]] began work on a peace treaty in Nikolsburg that led to the [[Treaty of Prague (1866)|Treaty of Prague]] in 1866.\n\n===Jewish Mikulov===\n:{{See also|Familianten}}\n[[File:V09p305001 Nikolsburg.jpg|260px|thumb|Jewish quarter (1900s)]]\n\nThe beginning of the Jewish settlement in Nikolsburg dates as far as 1421, when Jews were expelled from [[Vienna]] and the neighboring province of [[Lower Austria]] by the duke of Austria, [[Albert II of Germany]]. The refugees settled in the town situated close to the Austrian border, some {{convert|85|km|0|abbr=off}} from the [[Austria]]n capital, under the protection of the princes of Liechtenstein, and additional settlers were brought after the expulsions of the Jews from the Moravian royal boroughs by the king [[Ladislaus the Posthumous]] after 1454.<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\">Nezhodov\u00e1, So\u0148a. ''The Jewish Mikulov'' (\u017didovsk\u00fd Mikulov). 1. ed. Brno: Matice moravsk\u00e1, 2006, 423 p. {{ISBN|80-86488-28-4}}</ref>\n\nThe settlement grew in importance and in the first half of the 16th century Nikolsburg became the seat of the regional [[rabbi]] of [[Moravia]], thus becoming a cultural centre of Moravian Jewry. The famous rabbi [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel]] (1525 &ndash; 1609), who is said to have created the [[golem]] of [[Prague]], officiated here for twenty years as the second regional rabbi between 1553 and 1573.<ref>[http://travel.nytimes.com/2011/09/25/travel/in-the-czech-republic-moravia-and-its-castles.html?pagewanted=all Moravia and its castles]</ref> Cardinal [[Franz von Dietrichstein]], son of Adam von Dietrichstein, was a special protector of the Jews, whose taxes were necessary to finance the Thirty Years' War.<ref name=\"Jewish Encycl\">Jewish Encyclopedia, ''\"[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?letter=N&artid=292 Jewish Nikolsburg]\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref>\n\nIn the first half of the 18th century, the congregation in Nikolsburg totalled over 600 families, being the largest Jewish settlement in [[Moravia]]. The census of 1754 decreed by Empress [[Maria Theresa of Austria]] ascertained that there were some 620 families established in Nikolsburg, i.e. the Jewish population of about 3,000 comprised half of the town's inhabitants.<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\"/> Only a small number of Jews could make their living in the town as artisans; the rest had to become merchants. The congregation suffered severely during the [[Silesian wars]] (1740&ndash;1742, 1744&ndash;1745 and 1756&ndash;1763), when they had to furnish the monarchy with their share in the supertaxes exacted by the government of Maria Theresa from the Jews of Moravia.<ref name=\"Jewish Encycl\"/>\n\nQuite a number of Nikolsburg Jews continued to earn their livelihood in Vienna, where they were permitted to stay for some time on special passports. The freedom of residence, which was conceded to the Jews in Austria in 1848, reduced the number of resident Jews in Nikolsburg to less than one-third of the population which it contained at the time of its highest development. In 1904, there were 749 Jewish residents in the city, out of a total population of 8,192.<ref name=\"Jewish Encycl\"/> In 1938, prior to the [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia]], the city population totaled about 8,000 mostly German-speaking inhabitants. Out of these, 472 were Jewish at this time.<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\"/> The Jewish settlement in Nikolsburg ceased to exist during World War II, as only 110 managed to emigrate in time, and 327 of Mikulov's Jews did not survive the [[the Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name=\"Nezhodov\u00e1423\"/>\n\nFollowing World War II, the town's German population was brutally expelled in 1945-46 by the Czechoslovak government. In 1948, Mikulov's population was around 5,200.\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Mikulov 4826.jpg|260px|thumb|St. Sebastian Chapel on the Holy Hill (''Svat\u00fd Kope\u010dek'')]]\n[[File:Mikulov-Nicolsburg city seal.jpg|thumb|260px|upright|Mikulov (Nicolsburg) official seal, 1810]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" <hiddentext>generated with [[:de:Wikipedia:Helferlein/VBA-Macro for EXCEL tableconversion]] V1.7<\\hiddentext>\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|width=\"64\" height=\"14\"|Census year\n|width=\"60\" rowspan=\"2\"|Population\n|width=\"260\" colspan=\"3\"|Ethnicity of inhabitants\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"14\"|year\n|German\n|Czechs\n|other\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1793\n|7440\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1836\n|8421\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1869\n|7173\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1880\n|7642\n|7447\n|144\n|61\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1890\n|8210\n|8057\n|79\n|74\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1900\n|8092\n|7843\n|170\n|79\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1910\n|8043\n|7787\n|189\n|67\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1921\n|7699\n|6359\n|626\n|485\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"13\"|1930\n|7790\n|6409\n|898\n|483\n|- align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"\n|height=\"14\"|1939\n|7886\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|}<ref>Historick\u00fd m\u00edstopis Moravy a Slezska v letech 1848\u20131960, sv.9. 1984</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nMikulov is a centre of [[Czech wine|Czech wine-making]] due to its favorable geographic location and climate, as well as its unique history. Mikulov is not only the centre, but the namesake of, the Moravian wine sub-region ''vinarsk\u00e1 podoblast [[Mikulovsk\u00e1 wine|Mikulovsk\u00e1]]''.<ref>Wine of the Czech Republic, ''\"[http://www.wineofczechrepublic.cz/2-1-2-sub-region-mikulov-en.html Mikulov Wine Region] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719024934/http://www.wineofczechrepublic.cz/2-1-2-sub-region-mikulov-en.html |date=2011-07-19 }}\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref> Twelve registered [[cadastral]] vineyard tracts (Czech: ''trat'') are situated within the Mikulov wine village as defined under the Czech Viticulture Act.<ref>Czech Wine Law, ''\"[http://www.vinarskyfond.cz/legislativa/1-vinarska_legislativa_2004.pdf Viticulture Act of 2004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718190125/http://www.vinarskyfond.cz/legislativa/1-vinarska_legislativa_2004.pdf |date=2011-07-18 }}\"'', pg 87-90, Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref> Other significant economic activities in Mikulov are the machine-making and clay industries, as well as oil found at the edge of the [[Viennese Basin]].\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Mikulov, z\u00e1mek.JPG|thumb|260px|[[Mikulov Castle]]]]\nMikulov's historic buildings, such as [[Mikulov Castle]], and the surrounding wine country draw tourists from the Czech Republic and neighboring countries. Beginning in Mikulov, the 65 kilometer long [[Mikulov Wine Trail]] winds throughout the Mikulov wine region and is a part of [[wine tourism]] in the area. Other noteworthy historic sights are the [[Dietrichstein]] sepulchre, the old [[Jewish quarter (diaspora)|Jewish Quarter]], and the [[Piarist]] College. Several historic churches and a synagogue, built in various architectural styles, are located in Mikulov, including the [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] Church of St. V\u00e1clav and charnel house, the [[Baroque]] Church of St. John the Baptist, St. Sebastian Chapel on the Holy Hill (''Svat\u00fd Kope\u010dek''), the [[neo-Gothic]] Eastern Christian Church of St. Nicolas, and the Altschul Synagogue.\n\n==Notable people==\n===Born in Mikulov===\n* [[Johann Ferdinand Hertodt]] (1645\u20131722), German Moravian physician and writer\n* [[Moses ben Avraham Avinu]] (?\u20131733), printer, author, Christian convert to Judaism\n* [[Jakab Fellner|Jakob Fellner]] (1722\u20131780), German Moravian Baroque architect\n* [[Joseph von Sonnenfels]], n\u00e9 Lipmann (1732\u20131817), Austrian and German Jewish (later Christian) jurist, novelist\n* [[Anton Joseph Leeb]] (1769\u20131837), [[Mayor of Vienna]] (1835-1837)\n* [[Heinrich Landesmann]] (1821\u20131902), Austrian Jewish poet and philosophical writer\n* [[Heinrich Auspitz]] (1835\u20131886), Austrian Jewish dermatologist\n* [[Elkan Bauer]] (1852\u20131942), Austrian Jewish composer of popular waltzes\n* [[Edmund Wengraf]] (1860\u20131933, Vienna), Austrian jurist, journalist, narrative writer, novelist, essayist, poet, theatre critic\n* [[Siegfried Altmann]] (1872\u20131961), Austrian Jewish educator and former Director of Das Israelitisches Blindeninstitut, a Jewish institute for blind children.<ref>Center for Jewish History Digital Collections, ''\"[http://digital.cjh.org/R/?func=dbin-jump-full&object_id=431106&local_base=GEN01 Sigfried Altmann Collection]\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref>\n* [[Moriz Jung]] (1885\u20131915), Austrian painter and graphic artist, notable for his work for the [[Wiener Werkst\u00e4tte]]\n* [[Adolf Sch\u00e4rf]] (1890\u20131965), Austrian Social Democratic politician and President of Austria (1957-1965)\n* [[Manfred Ackermann]] (1898\u20131991), Austrian Social Democratic politician\n* [[Karel Krautgartner]] (1922\u20131982), Czech jazz and classical clarinetist, saxophonist, arranger, composer, conductor and teacher\n\n===Resided in Mikulov===\n* [[Balthasar Hubmaier]] (1480\u20131528), Moravian German Anabaptist ([[Schwertler]] [[:de:Schwertler|(de)]]) leader\n* [[Leonhard Schiemer]] (1500\u20131528), Austrian Anabaptist writer\n* [[Adam von Dietrichstein]] (1527\u20131590), purchaser of the Mikulov estate in 1575\n* [[Dietrichstein|Maximilian, Prince of Dietrichstein]] (1596\u20131655), grandson of Adam von Dietrichstein and owner of the Mikulov estate\n* [[Aaron Samuel Kaidanover]] (1614\u20131676), Polish-Lithuanian rabbi\n* [[Joseph Almosnino]] (1642\u20131689), Greek-Serbian rabbi\n* [[Judah he-Hasid (Jerusalem)|Judah he-Hasid]] (1660\u20131700), Jewish preacher\n* [[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin]] (1745\u20131815), Polish rabbi\n* [[Abraham Trebitsch]] (1760\u20131840), Austrian Jewish scholar\n* [[Simcha Bunim of Peshischa]] (1765\u20131827), Polish rabbi\n* [[Bonif\u00e1c Buzek]] (1788\u20131839) [[:de:Bonif\u00e1c Buzek|(de)]], Moravian priest\n* [[Abraham Neuda]] (1812\u20131854), Moravian rabbi\n* [[Simon Bacher]] (1823\u20131891), Hungarian Neo-Hebraic poet\n* [[Meyer Kayserling]] (1829\u20131905), German rabbi\n* [[Samuel Baeck]] (1834\u20131912), German rabbi\n* [[Karl Borrom\u00e4us Landsteiner|Karl (Carl) Borrom\u00e4us Landsteiner]] (''pseudonym: Arthur Landerstein''; 1835, Schlo\u00df Stoitzendorf, [[Stoitzendorf]] bei [[Eggenburg]], Lower Austria - 1909, Mikulov), Austrian [[Catholic theologian]], author<ref>aeiou Encyclopedia, ''\"[http://www.aeiou.at/aeiou.encyclop./l159167.htm;internal&action=_setlanguage.action?LANGUAGE=en Landsteiner, Karl]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\"'', Retrieved 2011-01-30</ref>\n* [[Karl Renner]] (1870\u20131950), Austrian Social Democratic politician, Chancellor of Austria (1918\u20131920, 1945), President of Austria (1945\u20131950)\n* [[Richard Teltscher]] (1888\u20131974), Austrian Jewish wine-merchant, patron and patriot, founder of the [[Jewish Central Museum for Moravia-Silesia]] in Mikulov\n\n===Rabbis===\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Judah L\u00f6w ben Bezaleel]], the first rabbi of Nikolsburg, chief rabbi of Moravia, officiated in Nikolsburg about 1553\u20131573\n* [[Judah L\u00f6b Eilenburg]] (1574\u20131618)\n* Gabriel ben Chajjim ben Sinaj (1618\u20131624)\n* [[Yom-\u1e6cob Lipmann Heller]] (1624\u2013 )\n* [[Pethahiah ben Joseph]] (1631\u20131637)\n* Abraham ben Mordechaj Jaffe (1637\u20131647)\n* [[Menahem Mendel Krochmal]] (1648\u20131661)\n* [[Gershon Ashkenazi]] (1661\u2013 )\n* [[Aaron Jacob ben Ezekiel]] ( \u20131671)\n* [[Judah L\u00f6b, son of Menahem Krochmal]] (1672\u20131684)\n* [[Eliezer Mendel Fanta]] (1684\u20131690)\n* [[David Oppenheim (rabbi)|David Oppenheim]] (1690\u20131702)\n* [[Gabriel Eskeles]] (1709\u20131718)\n* Bernard Eskeles (1718\u20131753)\n* Moses Lwow-Lemburger (1753\u20131757)\n* [[Gershon Politz]] (1757\u20131772)\n* [[Shmelke of Nikolsburg|Shmuel \"S(c)hmelke\" (ben Hirsh Halevi) Horowitz of Nikolsburg]] (1772\u20131778)\n* [[Gershon Chajes]] (1780\u20131789)\n* [[Mordecai Benet]] (1789\u20131829)\n* [[Nahum Trebitsch]] (1831\u20131842)\n* [[Samson Raphael Hirsch]] (1847\u20131851)\n* Hirsch Teltscher (1851\u20131853)\n* Isak Weinberger (1853\u20131855)\n* [[Solomon Quetsch]] (1855\u20131856)\n* [[Mayer Feuchtwang]] (1861\u20131888)\n* [[David Feuchtwang]] (1892\u20131903), also [[IKG Wien|chief rabbi of Vienna]]; Son of Mayer\n* [[Moritz Levin]] (since 1903\u20131918)\n* Alfred Willmann (1919\u20131938)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Czech Republic}}\n\nMikulov is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Partnersk\u00e1 m\u011bsta|url=http://www.mikulov.cz/mesto-mikulov/partnerska-mesta/|publisher=M\u011bsto Mikulov|language=cs|accessdate=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Bardejov]], [[Slovakia]] \n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Galanta]], [[Slovakia]]  \n*[[Katzrin]], [[Israeli settlement]] in the [[Golan Heights]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Laa an der Thaya]], [[Austria]]\n*{{flagicon|CZE}} [[\u0160umperk]], [[Czech Republic]]\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Tuch\u00f3w]], [[Poland]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Mikulov 2009 P1010966.jpg|Main square and sgraffit house\nFile:Mikulov 2009 P1010979.jpg|Main square view towards the chapel\nFile:Mikulov04.jpg|Castle in Mikulov\nFile:Mikulov Castle 2009 P1010969.jpg|Castle park\nFile:Mikulov, synagoga na ulici Husova.JPG|[[Synagogue (Mikulov)|Synagogue]] in the former Jewish quarter\nFile:Nikolsburg Obere Synagoge 2009 02.JPG|Synagogue, inside\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dietrichstein tomb]]\n* [[Lednice - Valtice area]]\n* [[Lednice\u2013Valtice Cultural Landscape]]\n* [[Old Hungarian script#Medieval Hungary|Old Hungarian alphabet of Nikolsburg]]\n* [[Ostlandkreuz]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Commons category|Jewish community in Mikulov}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Nikolsburg}}\n* [http://www.mikulov.cz/en/?languageId=1 Official Mikulov City Website]\n* [http://www.rmm.cz/index_en.html Mikulov Regional Museum]\n* [http://www.wineofczechrepublic.cz/en.html Wine of Czech Republic]\n* [https://www.amazingczechia.com/destinations/mikulov/ Presentation of Mikulov with a photo gallery]\n* [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?letter=N&artid=292 Nikolsburg (Jewish Encyclopedia)]\n* [http://www.nikolsburg.org Jewish Nikolsburg Organization]\n\n{{B\u0159eclav District}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Mikulov| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places in B\u0159eclav District]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Historic Jewish communities]]\n[[Category:Shtetls]]\n[[Category:Austria\u2013Czech Republic border crossings]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Czechoslovakia]]\n", "name_user": "Dvdgrv", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikulov"}
{"title_page": "OFB (group)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = OFB\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[London]]\n| genre            = [[British_hip_hop#UK_drill|UK drill]]\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[BisGotBlammed]]\n| website          = \n| alias            = Original Farm Boys\n}}\n\n{{short description|UK drill music group}}\n\n'''OFB''', also known as '''Original Farm Boys''', is a British [[drill music|drill]] group based in [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[North London]]. OFB is among one of the most prominent UK drill groups.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|title=UK drill rappers OFB: 'No one helps us round here. Music is the only way'|last=Thapar|first=Ciaran|date=2019-09-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217134655/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|archive-date=2019-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|title=The 20 best albums of 2019|last=Dazed|date=2019-12-11|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215164722/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|title=The Drop: The Best UK Drill of November 2019|date=2019-11-14|website=Passion of the Weiss|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182618/https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Headie One]] (formerly Headz) and [[RV (rapper)|RV]] (formerly Young RV) are among the most prominent members of the group. They were both originally rappers in Star Gang, a [[road rap]] group from the 2000s and split-off from the [[Tottenham Mandem]] gang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|title=Heart of a lion: the rise of Headie One|website=The Face|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108132845/https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|archive-date=2019-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> RV and Headie One have frequently collaborated with each other, including co-releasing the mixtapes ''Sticks & Stones'' (2016) and ''Drillers x Trappers'' (2017).<ref name=\"nme match day\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|title=Watch RV and Headie One's football-themed video for 'Match Day'|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=21 March 2019|work=[[NME]]|access-date=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324030654/https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|archive-date=24 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2018, Headie One released his solo mixtape, ''The One''. The mixtape included the song \"Know Better\" featuring [[RV (rapper)|RV]], which became an \"underground hit\". This was followed by another solo mixtape, ''The One Two'', in June 2018, which entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|title=The One Two|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119182750/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBandokay, DoubleLz, and SJ form a sub-group within OFB, initially using the name Y.OFB (Young OFB) signifying their status as younger members of the group, before later dropping the \"Y.\" and co-opting the \"OFB\" prefix older members of the group used.<ref name=\":2\" /> OFB rapper Bandokay, whos real name is Kemani Duggan, is the son of [[Death of Mark Duggan|Mark Duggan]], the man who's death by police shooting led to the [[2011 England riots|2011 England Riots]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Bandokay credited music for keeping him away from crime, and stated his desire to be away from police as a motivator:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=\"Whenever [the police] see me, they stop me, I get what they\u2019re trying to do \u2013 they\u2019re trying to take weapons. But I know they purposely stop me more than anyone else. They know who I am. They know who my dad is. So that\u2019s why I\u2019m trying to go through music and do something positive, so they don\u2019t have nothing to say about me.\"|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nBandokay credited fellow OFB rapper Headie One as a major influence, as well as UK drill group [[67 (rap group)|67]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2019, Headie One released \"18Hunna\", featuring [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]], which entered the UK chart at number 6 - the highest a drill artist has ever charted.<ref name=\"Headie One\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|title=Headie One|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=30 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121614/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Top40\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|title=Who is Headie One and what is the '18 Hunna' challenge?|date=15 January 2019|website=[[The Official Big Top 40]]|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121104/https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following RV's release from prison,<ref name=\"scan\">{{Cite web|url=https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|title=What Do You Mean You Haven't Heard Of... RV?|date=12 March 2019|website=[[SCAN (newspaper)|SCAN]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107193910/https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|archive-date=7 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> on 22 March 2019, RV and Headie One released a third mixtape called ''Drillers x Trappers II''.<ref name=\"complex\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|title=Headie One And RV Return With 'Drillers x Trappers II' Mixtape|last=Oke|first=Tobi|date=22 March 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=26 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326125431/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|archive-date=26 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 21.<ref name=\"drillers charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ \"Drillers and Trappers 2\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330143441/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ |date=2019-03-30 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">30 March</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> \"Match Day\", the first single from the mixtape, entered the Singles Chart at number 86.<ref name=\"match day charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ \"match day &#x7C; full Official Chart History\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107200729/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ |date=2019-11-07 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 November</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> He publicly revealed his face for the first time in the music video \"Why Always Me\".<ref name=\"the face\">{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|title=Bally On Me: Why UK drill rappers cover their faces|website=[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]|language=en-gb|access-date=24 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509164715/https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GRM brand new\">{{Cite news|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|title=Premiere: RV Makes Big Return With \"Brand New/Why Always Me\" Visuals|last=Wynter|first=Courtney|date=28 February 2019|work=[[GRM Daily]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608221347/http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|archive-date=8 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the OFB released their first collective mixtape titled \"Frontstreet\", named after a road in Broadwater Farm that locals call \"Front Street\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> [[Dazed|Dazed Digital]] called the mixtape \"one of the best British debuts of the decade\".<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2019, following the release of (OFB member) SJ's \"Youngest In Charge\", it was revealed SJ was currently facing trial for a murder charge and had been arrested.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: Bandokay and Double Lz's \"Mad About Bars\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref> SJ was later convicted and sentenced to life with a minimum of 21 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.met.police.uk/news/five-jailed-for-wood-green-murder-392682|title=Five jailed for Wood Green murder|website=Mynewsdesk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nLike many other drill groups, OFB has had its songs taken down by YouTube at request of the [[Metropolitan Police Service|metropolitan police]]. In 2019, OFB's own YouTube channel was also taken down, before later being reinstated the next day. Bandokay stated they were trying to clean up their music in order to avoid takedowns.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Members ==\nThe list below includes confirmed members of OFB<!--Do not add members without a reliable source confirming they are members.-->:{{div col}}\n* Akz\n* Bandokay<ref name=\":0\" /> (son of [[Mark Duggan]])\n* Bradz \n* Dee One<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|title=OFB's Dee One Delivers Cold 'Next Up? Freestyle|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Dezzie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|title=Dezzie unveils brand-new 'Bad Breed' visuals|website=Link Up Tv|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191453/https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Double Lz<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Dsavvv\n* [[Headie One]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|title=The New New: 14 U.K. Rappers You Should Know - XXL|last=Rathod|first=Nikita|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Izzpot<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-izzpot-free-s|title=OFB's Izzpot drops visuals for new track \"Free S\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n* JS<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|title=OFB's JS Releases \"Young Rich\" Visuals|website=www.mixtapemadness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kash<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/kash-you-alright|title=OFB's Kash asks \"You Alright?\" in latest video|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191455/http://grmdaily.com/video/kash-you-alright|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kush<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-kush-no-biggie|title=OFB's Kush provides hard tune \"No Biggie\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-kush-no-biggie|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Lowkey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plugsville.com/drillers-x-trappers-ii-rv-headie-one-mixtape-match-day/|title=Drillers x Trappers II: RV and Headie One release mixtape and 'Match Day'|date=2019-03-22|website=Plugsville|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215192953/https://www.plugsville.com/drillers-x-trappers-ii-rv-headie-one-mixtape-match-day/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Munie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/ofb-munie-lightwork-freestyle-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: OFB Munie's \"Lightwork Freestyle\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191452/https://pitchfork.com/levels/ofb-munie-lightwork-freestyle-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[RV_(rapper)|RV]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/knife-attackers-use-youtube-to-issue-death-threats-from-prison-rxq9pkqll|title=Knife attackers use YouTube to issue death threats from prison|last=Shingi\u00a0Mararike|first=Tom Harper and|date=2019-03-10|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en|issn=0956-1382|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824194613/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/knife-attackers-use-youtube-to-issue-death-threats-from-prison-rxq9pkqll|archive-date=2019-08-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* SJ<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Skat<ref>{{Cite \nweb|url=https://versus.uk.com/2018/10/headie-one-links-skat-ofb-collab-water/|title=Headie One Links Up with Skat for OFB Collab, \"Water\"|date=2018-10-15|website=VERSUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191455/https://versus.uk.com/2018/10/headie-one-links-skat-ofb-collab-water/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Zilla<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/munie-zilla-cant-save-these-shots|title=OFB's Munie & Zilla join forces for \"Can't Save These Shots\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/http://grmdaily.com/video/munie-zilla-cant-save-these-shots|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:UK drill musicians]]\n[[Category:Tottenham]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = OFB\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[London]]\n| genre            = [[British_hip_hop#UK_drill|UK drill]]\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Harlem Spartans]]\n| website          = \n| alias            = Original Farm Boys\n}}\n\n{{short description|UK drill music group}}\n\n'''OFB''', also known as '''Original Farm Boys''', is a British [[drill music|drill]] group based in [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[North London]]. OFB is among one of the most prominent UK drill groups.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|title=UK drill rappers OFB: 'No one helps us round here. Music is the only way'|last=Thapar|first=Ciaran|date=2019-09-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217134655/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|archive-date=2019-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|title=The 20 best albums of 2019|last=Dazed|date=2019-12-11|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215164722/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|title=The Drop: The Best UK Drill of November 2019|date=2019-11-14|website=Passion of the Weiss|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182618/https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Headie One]] (formerly Headz) and [[RV (rapper)|RV]] (formerly Young RV) are among the most prominent members of the group. They were both originally rappers in Star Gang, a [[road rap]] group from the 2000s and split-off from the [[Tottenham Mandem]] gang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|title=Heart of a lion: the rise of Headie One|website=The Face|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108132845/https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|archive-date=2019-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> RV and Headie One have frequently collaborated with each other, including co-releasing the mixtapes ''Sticks & Stones'' (2016) and ''Drillers x Trappers'' (2017).<ref name=\"nme match day\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|title=Watch RV and Headie One's football-themed video for 'Match Day'|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=21 March 2019|work=[[NME]]|access-date=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324030654/https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|archive-date=24 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2018, Headie One released his solo mixtape, ''The One''. The mixtape included the song \"Know Better\" featuring [[RV (rapper)|RV]], which became an \"underground hit\". This was followed by another solo mixtape, ''The One Two'', in June 2018, which entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|title=The One Two|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119182750/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBandokay, DoubleLz, and SJ form a sub-group within OFB, initially using the name Y.OFB (Young OFB) signifying their status as younger members of the group, before later dropping the \"Y.\" and co-opting the \"OFB\" prefix older members of the group used.<ref name=\":2\" /> OFB rapper Bandokay, whos real name is Kemani Duggan, is the son of [[Death of Mark Duggan|Mark Duggan]], the man who's death by police shooting led to the [[2011 England riots|2011 England Riots]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Bandokay credited music for keeping him away from crime, and stated his desire to be away from police as a motivator:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=\"Whenever [the police] see me, they stop me, I get what they\u2019re trying to do \u2013 they\u2019re trying to take weapons. But I know they purposely stop me more than anyone else. They know who I am. They know who my dad is. So that\u2019s why I\u2019m trying to go through music and do something positive, so they don\u2019t have nothing to say about me.\"|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nBandokay credited fellow OFB rapper Headie One as a major influence, as well as UK drill group [[67 (rap group)|67]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2019, Headie One released \"18Hunna\", featuring [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]], which entered the UK chart at number 6 - the highest a drill artist has ever charted.<ref name=\"Headie One\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|title=Headie One|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=30 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121614/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Top40\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|title=Who is Headie One and what is the '18 Hunna' challenge?|date=15 January 2019|website=[[The Official Big Top 40]]|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121104/https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following RV's release from prison,<ref name=\"scan\">{{Cite web|url=https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|title=What Do You Mean You Haven't Heard Of... RV?|date=12 March 2019|website=[[SCAN (newspaper)|SCAN]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107193910/https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|archive-date=7 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> on 22 March 2019, RV and Headie One released a third mixtape called ''Drillers x Trappers II''.<ref name=\"complex\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|title=Headie One And RV Return With 'Drillers x Trappers II' Mixtape|last=Oke|first=Tobi|date=22 March 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=26 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326125431/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|archive-date=26 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 21.<ref name=\"drillers charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ \"Drillers and Trappers 2\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330143441/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ |date=2019-03-30 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">30 March</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> \"Match Day\", the first single from the mixtape, entered the Singles Chart at number 86.<ref name=\"match day charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ \"match day &#x7C; full Official Chart History\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107200729/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ |date=2019-11-07 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 November</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> He publicly revealed his face for the first time in the music video \"Why Always Me\".<ref name=\"the face\">{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|title=Bally On Me: Why UK drill rappers cover their faces|website=[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]|language=en-gb|access-date=24 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509164715/https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GRM brand new\">{{Cite news|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|title=Premiere: RV Makes Big Return With \"Brand New/Why Always Me\" Visuals|last=Wynter|first=Courtney|date=28 February 2019|work=[[GRM Daily]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608221347/http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|archive-date=8 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the OFB released their first collective mixtape titled \"Frontstreet\", named after a road in Broadwater Farm that locals call \"Front Street\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> [[Dazed|Dazed Digital]] called the mixtape \"one of the best British debuts of the decade\".<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2019, following the release of (OFB member) SJ's \"Youngest In Charge\", it was revealed SJ was currently facing trial for a murder charge and had been arrested.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: Bandokay and Double Lz's \"Mad About Bars\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref> SJ was later convicted and sentenced to life with a minimum of 21 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.met.police.uk/news/five-jailed-for-wood-green-murder-392682|title=Five jailed for Wood Green murder|website=Mynewsdesk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nLike many other drill groups, OFB has had its songs taken down by YouTube at request of the [[Metropolitan Police Service|metropolitan police]]. In 2019, OFB's own YouTube channel was also taken down, before later being reinstated the next day. Bandokay stated they were trying to clean up their music in order to avoid takedowns.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Members ==\nThe list below includes confirmed members of OFB<!--Do not add members without a reliable source confirming they are members.-->:{{div col}}\n* Akz\n* Bandokay<ref name=\":0\" /> (son of [[Mark Duggan]])\n* Bradz \n* Dee One<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|title=OFB's Dee One Delivers Cold 'Next Up? Freestyle|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Dezzie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|title=Dezzie unveils brand-new 'Bad Breed' visuals|website=Link Up Tv|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191453/https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Double Lz<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Dsavvv\n* [[Headie One]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|title=The New New: 14 U.K. Rappers You Should Know - XXL|last=Rathod|first=Nikita|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Izzpot<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-izzpot-free-s|title=OFB's Izzpot drops visuals for new track \"Free S\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n* JS<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|title=OFB's JS Releases \"Young Rich\" Visuals|website=www.mixtapemadness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kash<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/kash-you-alright|title=OFB's Kash asks \"You Alright?\" in latest video|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191455/http://grmdaily.com/video/kash-you-alright|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kush<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-kush-no-biggie|title=OFB's Kush provides hard tune \"No Biggie\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-kush-no-biggie|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Lowkey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plugsville.com/drillers-x-trappers-ii-rv-headie-one-mixtape-match-day/|title=Drillers x Trappers II: RV and Headie One release mixtape and 'Match Day'|date=2019-03-22|website=Plugsville|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215192953/https://www.plugsville.com/drillers-x-trappers-ii-rv-headie-one-mixtape-match-day/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Munie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/ofb-munie-lightwork-freestyle-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: OFB Munie's \"Lightwork Freestyle\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191452/https://pitchfork.com/levels/ofb-munie-lightwork-freestyle-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[RV_(rapper)|RV]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/knife-attackers-use-youtube-to-issue-death-threats-from-prison-rxq9pkqll|title=Knife attackers use YouTube to issue death threats from prison|last=Shingi\u00a0Mararike|first=Tom Harper and|date=2019-03-10|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en|issn=0956-1382|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824194613/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/knife-attackers-use-youtube-to-issue-death-threats-from-prison-rxq9pkqll|archive-date=2019-08-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* SJ<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Skat<ref>{{Cite \nweb|url=https://versus.uk.com/2018/10/headie-one-links-skat-ofb-collab-water/|title=Headie One Links Up with Skat for OFB Collab, \"Water\"|date=2018-10-15|website=VERSUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191455/https://versus.uk.com/2018/10/headie-one-links-skat-ofb-collab-water/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Zilla<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/munie-zilla-cant-save-these-shots|title=OFB's Munie & Zilla join forces for \"Can't Save These Shots\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/http://grmdaily.com/video/munie-zilla-cant-save-these-shots|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:UK drill musicians]]\n[[Category:Tottenham]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n", "name_user": "86.6.39.70", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OFB_(group)"}
{"title_page": "Kick Out the Jams", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Kick Out the Jams\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[MC5]]\n| cover      = MC5 - Kick Out the Jams.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 1969\n| recorded   = October 30\u201331, 1968\n| venue      = [[Grande Ballroom]], Detroit, Michigan\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{Hlist|[[Proto-punk]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XG9CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA411|title=The 100 Greatest Bands of All Time: A Guide to the Legends Who Rocked the World|last=Moskowitz|first=David V.|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-0340-6|page=411}}</ref>|[[garage rock]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CaVBRNleMKsC&pg=PA77|title=Traveling Music: The Soundtrack to My Life and Times|last=Peart|first=Neil|date=2004|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55490-795-3|page=77}}</ref>|[[hard rock]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/newbookofrocklis00mars|url-access=registration|title=New Book of Rock Lists|last=Marsh|first=Dave|last2=Bernard|first2=James|date=1994|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-671-78700-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/newbookofrocklis00mars/page/391 391]}}</ref>|[[punk rock]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DykffzkFALoC&pg=PA665|title=Rock Obituaries: Knocking On Heaven's Door|last=Talevski|first=Nick|date=2010|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-117-2|page=665}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 39:52\n| label      = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n| producer   = [[Jac Holzman]], [[Bruce Botnick]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Back in the USA (album)|Back in the USA]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n'''''Kick Out the Jams''''' is the debut album by American [[proto-punk]] band [[MC5]]. It was released in February 1969, through [[Elektra Records]]. It was recorded live at Detroit's [[Grande Ballroom]] over two nights, [[Devil's Night]] and [[Halloween]], 1968. \n\nThe LP peaked at No. 30 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with the [[Kick Out the Jams (song)|title track]] peaking at No. 82 in the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. Although the album received an unfavorable review in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine upon its release, it has gone on to be considered an important forerunner to [[punk rock]] music, and in 2003 was ranked number 294 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'s}} \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]\" list,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/kick-out-the-jams-mc5-19691231 |title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: MC5, <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Kick Out the Jams''<nowiki>'</nowiki> &#124; ''Rolling Stone'' |work=[[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]] |accessdate=February 17, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705020104/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/mc5-kick-out-the-jams-19691231 |archivedate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> and 294 in a 2012 revised list.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/mc5-kick-out-the-jams-31238/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 9, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Release==\nThe album peaked at number 30 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' albums]] chart, \"in the wake of a publicity blitz\", wrote [[Robert Christgau]] in ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981).<ref>{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=0899190251|chapter=The Guide|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bk-cg70/guide.php|accessdate=March 30, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n\nWhile \"Ramblin' Rose\" and \"Motor City Is Burning\" open with the band's typical leftist and revolutionary rhetoric, it was the opening line to the title track that stirred up controversy. Vocalist [[Rob Tyner]] shouted, \"And right now... right now... right now it's time to... kick out the jams, motherfuckers!\" before the opening riffs. [[Elektra Records]] executives were offended by the line and had preferred to edit it out of the album (replacing the offending words with \"brothers and sisters\"), while the band and manager [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]] adamantly opposed this.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}\n\nThe original release had \"kick out the jams, Motherfuckers!\" printed on the inside album cover, but was soon pulled from stores. Two versions were then released, both with censored album covers, with the uncensored audio version sold behind record counters.\n\nMaking matters worse, [[Hudson's]] department stores refused to carry the album. Tensions between the band and the Hudson's chain escalated to the point that the department stores refused to carry any album from the Elektra label after MC5 took out a full-page ad that, according to [[Danny Fields]], \"was just a picture of Rob Tyner, and all it said was 'Fuck Hudson's.' And it had the Elektra logo\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=McNeil |first1=Legs |authorlink=Legs McNeil |last2=McCain |first2=Gillian |title=Please Kill Me: The Uncensored Oral History of Punk |publisher=Penguin Books |year=1996 |page=62}}</ref> To end the conflict and to avoid further financial loss, Elektra dropped MC5 from their record label.\n\nLater the same year, [[Jefferson Airplane]] recorded the song \"We Can Be Together\" for their ''[[Volunteers (Jefferson Airplane album)|Volunteers]]'' album, a song containing the word \"motherfucker\". Unlike Elektra, RCA Records released the album wholly uncensored.\n\n==Title meaning==\n\n\"Kick out the jams\" has also been taken to be a slogan of the 1960s ethos of revolution and liberation, an incitement to \"kick out\" restrictions in various forms.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} To quote MC5 guitarist [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]] from his interview with Caroline Boucher in ''[[Disc (magazine)|Disc & Music Echo]]'' magazine on August 8, 1970:\n\n<blockquote>People said \"oh wow, 'kick out the jams' means break down restrictions\" etc., and it made good copy, but when we wrote it we didn't have that in mind. We first used the phrase when we were the house band at a ballroom in Detroit, and we played there every week with another band from the area. [...] We got in the habit, being the sort of punks we are, of screaming at them to get off the stage, to kick out the jams, meaning stop jamming. We were saying it all the time and it became a sort of esoteric phrase. Now, I think people can get what they like out of it; that's one of the good things about rock and roll.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Caroline |last=Boucher |date=August 8, 1970 |title=MC5 Problem |journal=[[Disc (magazine)|Disc & Music Echo]] |url=http://makemyday.free.fr/discandme.htm |accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nKramer also claimed during a 1999 interview that was excerpted for ''[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]]'' magazine that the phrase was specifically aimed toward British 1960s bands playing at the Grande who MC5 felt were not putting enough energy into their performances.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} The title has also (jokingly) been reinterpreted as an establishment message masquerading as a revolutionary anthem. [[David Bowie]] sings in the song \"[[Cygnet Committee]]\": \"[We] stoned the poor on slogans such as/Wish You Could Hear/Love Is All We Need/Kick Out the Jams/Kick Out Your Mother\".\n\n==Critical reception==\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/kick-out-the-jams-mw0000263578 |title=Kick Out the Jams |author=Deming, Mark |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2score = (unfavorable)<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite journal |title=MC5 |date=April 5, 1969 |author=[[Lester Bangs|Bangs, Lester]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/kick-out-the-jams-19690405 |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=San Francisco |publisher=Straight Arrow Publishers, Inc. |accessdate=February 26, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev3score = (very favorable)<ref name=PopMatters>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/mc5-kickoutthejams |title=MC5: Kick out the Jams |author=Williams, Adam |date=September 4, 2003 |work=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = Treble\n| rev4score = (favorable)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.treblezine.com/reviews/296.html |title=MC5 |author=Drozdowski, Wilson |date=September 23, 2004 |work=Treble |accessdate=February 17, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120164400/http://www.treblezine.com/reviews/296.html |archivedate=November 20, 2008}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n}}\n\nUpon its release, critic [[Lester Bangs]], writing his inaugural review for ''Rolling Stone'', called ''Kick Out the Jams'' a \"ridiculous, overbearing, pretentious album\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> In contrast to this view, modern opinion of the album generally holds it in very high regard, noting its influence on rock music that has followed. [[Allmusic]] called it \"one of the most powerfully energetic live albums ever made\" in their retrospective review.<ref name=Allmusic/> ''[[PopMatters]]'' reviewer Adam Williams wrote, \"For my money, 'Kick Out the Jams' is one of the greatest records ever pressed. It is a magnificent time portal into the past, a fleeting glimpse of a band that actually had the balls to walk it like they talked it\" and that \"no live recording has captured the primal elements of rock more than the MC5's inaugural effort.\"<ref name=PopMatters/>. Bangs himself would change his mind about the album, writing in a footnote in his [[The Troggs|Troggs]] essay \u201cJames Taylor Marked for Death\u201d: \u201cIncidentally, I\u2019m not trying to run down the Five, or write them off as some Troggs trifle. When I reviewed their first album in ''Rolling Stone'', I finished by mentioning \u201cThe Troggs, who appeared with a similar sex-and-violence thing a couple of years back, and promptly sank into oblivion, where I imagine they are laughing at the MC5,\u201d and that of course is as snottily unkind to the Troggs as to the Five. But then, it was the first review I ever had published, and even if more death threats came in after that review than any other save Jann Wenner's ''[[Wheels of Fire]]'' massacre (and most of them from sweet home Detroit), I can see why people privileged enough to be part of the apocalyptic birth of the Five would be enraged. And to compound the irony, ''Kick Out the Jams'' has been my favorite album or at least one of the two or three most played for about three months now.\u201d<ref>[[Lester Bangs|Bangs, Lester]] (2001). ''[[Psychotic Reactions and Carburetor Dung]].'' Serpent\u2019s Tail. p. 56. Reprint of 1971 ''[[Who Put the Bomp]]'' article.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe album cover is briefly visible in the 1986 music video of \"[[Don't Want to Know If You Are Lonely]]\" by [[H\u00fcsker D\u00fc]].\n\nIn March 2005, [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] placed the song \"Kick Out the Jams\" at number 39 in its \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks\" list. The same track was named the 65th best hard rock song of all time by [[VH1]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = MC5 ([[Rob Tyner]], [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]], [[Fred \"Sonic\" Smith]], [[Michael Davis (bassist)|Michael Davis]], [[Dennis Thompson (drummer)|Dennis Thompson]]), except as noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1 = Ramblin' Rose\n| writer1 = Fred Burch, [[Marijohn Wilkin]]\n| length1 = 4:15\n| title2 = [[Kick Out the Jams (song)|Kick Out the Jams]]\n| length2 = 2:52\n| title3 = Come Together\n| length3 = 4:29\n| title4 = Rocket Reducer No. 62 (Rama Lama Fa Fa Fa)\n| length4 = 5:41\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title5 = Borderline\n| length5 = 2:45\n| title6 = Motor City Is Burning\n| writer6 = Al Smith | length6 = 6:04\n| title7 = I Want You Right Now\n| writer7 = [[Colin Frechter]], [[Larry Page (British singer and manager)|Larry Page]]\n| length7 = 5:31\n| title8 = Starship\n| writer8 = MC5, [[Sun Ra]]\n| length8 = 8:15\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n; MC5\n\n* [[Rob Tyner]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]] \u2013 [[lead guitar|lead]] guitar, backing vocals, lead vocals on \"Ramblin' Rose\"\n* [[Fred \"Sonic\" Smith]] \u2013 [[rhythm guitar|rhythm]] guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Michael Davis (bassist)|Michael Davis]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Dennis Thompson (drummer)|Dennis Thompson]] \u2013 drums\n\n; Additional personnel\n\n* Brother J. C. Crawford \u2013 \"spiritual advisor\"\n* [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]] - \"guidance\", liner notes\n* [[Bruce Botnick]] - engineer\n* Robert L. Heimall, William S. Harvey - artwork\n* [[Joel Brodsky]] \u2013 album cover photo\n* [[Leni Sinclair|Magdalena Sinclair]] - liner photography\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=June 5, 1969|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/rock/mc5-69.php|title=The Continuing Saga of the MC-5|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|type=album|64011}}\n\n{{Mc5}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n[[Category:MC5 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jac Holzman]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bruce Botnick]]\n[[Category:1969 live albums]]\n[[Category:Live protopunk albums]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records live albums]]\n[[Category:1969 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Joel Brodsky]]\n[[Category:Acid rock albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Kick Out the Jams\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[MC5]]\n| cover      = MC5 - Kick Out the Jams.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 1969\n| recorded   = October 30\u201331, 1968\n| venue      = [[Grande Ballroom]], Detroit, Michigan\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{Hlist|[[Proto-punk]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XG9CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA411|title=The 100 Greatest Bands of All Time: A Guide to the Legends Who Rocked the World|last=Moskowitz|first=David V.|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-0340-6|page=411}}</ref>|[[garage rock]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CaVBRNleMKsC&pg=PA77|title=Traveling Music: The Soundtrack to My Life and Times|last=Peart|first=Neil|date=2004|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55490-795-3|page=77}}</ref>|[[hard rock]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/newbookofrocklis00mars|url-access=registration|title=New Book of Rock Lists|last=Marsh|first=Dave|last2=Bernard|first2=James|date=1994|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-671-78700-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/newbookofrocklis00mars/page/391 391]}}</ref>|[[punk rock]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DykffzkFALoC&pg=PA665|title=Rock Obituaries: Knocking On Heaven's Door|last=Talevski|first=Nick|date=2010|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-117-2|page=665}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 39:52\n| label      = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n| producer   = [[Jac Holzman]], [[Bruce Botnick]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Back in the USA (album)|Back in the USA]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n'''''Kick Out the Jams''''' is the debut album by American [[proto-punk]] band [[MC5]]. It was released in February 1969, through [[Elektra Records]]. It was recorded live at Detroit's [[Grande Ballroom]] over two nights, [[Devil's Night]] and [[Halloween]], 1968. \n\nThe LP peaked at No. 30 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with the [[Kick Out the Jams (song)|title track]] peaking at No. 82 in the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. Although the album received an unfavorable review in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine upon its release, it has gone on to be considered an important forerunner to [[punk rock]] music, and in 2003 was ranked number 294 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'s}} \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]\" list,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/kick-out-the-jams-mc5-19691231 |title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: MC5, <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Kick Out the Jams''<nowiki>'</nowiki> &#124; ''Rolling Stone'' |work=[[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]] |accessdate=February 17, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705020104/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/mc5-kick-out-the-jams-19691231 |archivedate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> and 294 in a 2012 revised list.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/mc5-kick-out-the-jams-31238/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 9, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Release==\nThe album peaked at number 30 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' albums]] chart, \"in the wake of a publicity blitz\", wrote [[Robert Christgau]] in ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981).<ref>{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=0899190251|chapter=The Guide|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bk-cg70/guide.php|accessdate=March 30, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n\nWhile \"Ramblin' Rose\" and \"Motor City Is Burning\" open with the band's typical leftist and revolutionary rhetoric, it was the opening line to the title track that stirred up controversy. Vocalist [[Rob Tyner]] shouted, \"And right now... right now... right now it's time to... kick out the jams, motherfuckers!\" before the opening riffs. [[Elektra Records]] executives were offended by the line and had preferred to edit it out of the album (replacing the offending words with \"brothers and sisters\"), while the band and manager [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]] adamantly opposed this.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}\n\nThe original release had \"kick out the jams, Motherfuckers!\" printed on the inside album cover, but was soon pulled from stores. Two versions were then released, both with censored album covers, with the uncensored audio version sold behind record counters.\n\nMaking matters worse, [[Hudson's]] department stores refused to carry the album. Tensions between the band and the Hudson's chain escalated to the point that the department stores refused to carry any album from the Elektra label after MC5 took out a full-page ad that, according to [[Danny Fields]], \"was just a picture of Rob Tyner, and all it said was 'Fuck Hudson's.' And it had the Elektra logo\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=McNeil |first1=Legs |authorlink=Legs McNeil |last2=McCain |first2=Gillian |title=Please Kill Me: The Uncensored Oral History of Punk |publisher=Penguin Books |year=1996 |page=62}}</ref> To end the conflict and to avoid further financial loss, Elektra dropped MC5 from their record label.\n\nLater the same year, [[Jefferson Airplane]] recorded the song \"We Can Be Together\" for their ''[[Volunteers (Jefferson Airplane album)|Volunteers]]'' album, a song containing the word \"motherfucker\". Unlike Elektra, RCA Records released the album wholly uncensored.\n\n==Title meaning==\n\n\"Kick out the jams\" has also been taken to be a slogan of the 1960s ethos of revolution and liberation, an incitement to \"kick out\" restrictions in various forms.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} To quote MC5 guitarist [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]] from his interview with Caroline Boucher in ''[[Disc (magazine)|Disc & Music Echo]]'' magazine on August 8, 1970:\n\n<blockquote>People said \"oh wow, 'kick out the jams' means break down restrictions\" etc., and it made good copy, but when we wrote it we didn't have that in mind. We first used the phrase when we were the house band at a ballroom in Detroit, and we played there every week with another band from the area. [...] We got in the habit, being the sort of punks we are, of screaming at them to get off the stage, to kick out the jams, meaning stop jamming. We were saying it all the time and it became a sort of esoteric phrase. Now, I think people can get what they like out of it; that's one of the good things about rock and roll.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Caroline |last=Boucher |date=August 8, 1970 |title=MC5 Problem |journal=[[Disc (magazine)|Disc & Music Echo]] |url=http://makemyday.free.fr/discandme.htm |accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nKramer also claimed during a 1999 interview that was excerpted for ''[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]]'' magazine that the phrase was specifically aimed toward British 1960s bands playing at the Grande who MC5 felt were not putting enough energy into their performances.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} The title has also (jokingly) been reinterpreted as an establishment message masquerading as a revolutionary anthem. [[David Bowie]] sings in the song \"[[Cygnet Committee]]\": \"[We] stoned the poor on slogans such as/Wish You Could Hear/Love Is All We Need/Kick Out the Jams/Kick Out Your Mother\".\n\n==Critical reception==\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/kick-out-the-jams-mw0000263578 |title=Kick Out the Jams |author=Deming, Mark |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2score = (unfavorable)<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite journal |title=MC5 |date=April 5, 1969 |author=[[Lester Bangs|Bangs, Lester]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/kick-out-the-jams-19690405 |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=San Francisco |publisher=Straight Arrow Publishers, Inc. |accessdate=February 26, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev3score = (very favorable)<ref name=PopMatters>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/mc5-kickoutthejams |title=MC5: Kick out the Jams |author=Williams, Adam |date=September 4, 2003 |work=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=February 17, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = Treble\n| rev4score = (favorable)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.treblezine.com/reviews/296.html |title=MC5 |author=Drozdowski, Wilson |date=September 23, 2004 |work=Treble |accessdate=February 17, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120164400/http://www.treblezine.com/reviews/296.html |archivedate=November 20, 2008}}</ref>\n}}\n\nUpon its release, critic [[Lester Bangs]], writing his inaugural review for ''Rolling Stone'', called ''Kick Out the Jams'' a \"ridiculous, overbearing, pretentious album\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> In contrast to this view, modern opinion of the album generally holds it in very high regard, noting its influence on rock music that has followed. [[Allmusic]] called it \"one of the most powerfully energetic live albums ever made\" in their retrospective review.<ref name=Allmusic/> ''[[PopMatters]]'' reviewer Adam Williams wrote, \"For my money, 'Kick Out the Jams' is one of the greatest records ever pressed. It is a magnificent time portal into the past, a fleeting glimpse of a band that actually had the balls to walk it like they talked it\" and that \"no live recording has captured the primal elements of rock more than the MC5's inaugural effort.\"<ref name=PopMatters/>. Bangs himself would change his mind about the album, writing in a footnote in his [[The Troggs|Troggs]] essay \u201cJames Taylor Marked for Death\u201d: \u201cIncidentally, I\u2019m not trying to run down the Five, or write them off as some Troggs trifle. When I reviewed their first album in ''Rolling Stone'', I finished by mentioning \u201cThe Troggs, who appeared with a similar sex-and-violence thing a couple of years back, and promptly sank into oblivion, where I imagine they are laughing at the MC5,\u201d and that of course is as snottily unkind to the Troggs as to the Five. But then, it was the first review I ever had published, and even if more death threats came in after that review than any other save Jann Wenner's ''[[Wheels of Fire]]'' massacre (and most of them from sweet home Detroit), I can see why people privileged enough to be part of the apocalyptic birth of the Five would be enraged. And to compound the irony, ''Kick Out the Jams'' has been my favorite album or at least one of the two or three most played for about three months now.\u201d<ref>[[Lester Bangs|Bangs, Lester]] (2001). ''[[Psychotic Reactions and Carburetor Dung]].'' Serpent\u2019s Tail. p. 56. Reprint of 1971 ''[[Who Put the Bomp]]'' article.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe album cover is briefly visible in the 1986 music video of \"[[Don't Want to Know If You Are Lonely]]\" by [[H\u00fcsker D\u00fc]].\n\nIn March 2005, [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] placed the song \"Kick Out the Jams\" at number 39 in its \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks\" list. The same track was named the 65th best hard rock song of all time by [[VH1]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = MC5 ([[Rob Tyner]], [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]], [[Fred \"Sonic\" Smith]], [[Michael Davis (bassist)|Michael Davis]], [[Dennis Thompson (drummer)|Dennis Thompson]]), except as noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1 = Ramblin' Rose\n| writer1 = Fred Burch, [[Marijohn Wilkin]]\n| length1 = 4:15\n| title2 = [[Kick Out the Jams (song)|Kick Out the Jams]]\n| length2 = 2:52\n| title3 = Come Together\n| length3 = 4:29\n| title4 = Rocket Reducer No. 62 (Rama Lama Fa Fa Fa)\n| length4 = 5:41\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title5 = Borderline\n| length5 = 2:45\n| title6 = Motor City Is Burning\n| writer6 = Al Smith | length6 = 6:04\n| title7 = I Want You Right Now\n| writer7 = [[Colin Frechter]], [[Larry Page (British singer and manager)|Larry Page]]\n| length7 = 5:31\n| title8 = Starship\n| writer8 = MC5, [[Sun Ra]]\n| length8 = 8:15\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n; MC5\n\n* [[Rob Tyner]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]] \u2013 [[lead guitar|lead]] guitar, backing vocals, lead vocals on \"Ramblin' Rose\"\n* [[Fred \"Sonic\" Smith]] \u2013 [[rhythm guitar|rhythm]] guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Michael Davis (bassist)|Michael Davis]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Dennis Thompson (drummer)|Dennis Thompson]] \u2013 drums\n\n; Additional personnel\n\n* Brother J. C. Crawford \u2013 \"spiritual advisor\"\n* [[John Sinclair (poet)|John Sinclair]] - \"guidance\", liner notes\n* [[Bruce Botnick]] - engineer\n* Robert L. Heimall, William S. Harvey - artwork\n* [[Joel Brodsky]] \u2013 album cover photo\n* [[Leni Sinclair|Magdalena Sinclair]] - liner photography\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=June 5, 1969|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/rock/mc5-69.php|title=The Continuing Saga of the MC-5|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|type=album|64011}}\n\n{{Mc5}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n[[Category:MC5 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jac Holzman]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bruce Botnick]]\n[[Category:1969 